No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today rejected a motion to abolish the paragraph on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko was convicted as part of an amendment to the penal code.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned ex-prime minister, was rejected by MEPs at the second reading of the motion to mitigate penalties for economic offences.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for concluding an allegedly adverse contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, in December the appeal of the convicted is to be heard in court.
Timoshenko himself describes the verdict as political revenge by the regime, and in the West, too, the trial raised suspicions of the court's bias.
The motion to remove paragraph 365, on the basis of which the former prime minister was convicted, from the penal code was supported by 147 MPs.
226 votes would have been required for its adoption.
