Beginning of a new crisis era
France and the rest of Europe in the focus of investors.
On Tuesday, a statistical storm raged through Europe.
The individual countries published their data on their GDP for the 3rd quarter.
The Czech economy stagnated compared to the previous quarter, while Germany and France are growing.
Today, however, the bond market is breaking all records.
Investors are keeping an eye not only on Greece, but now also on Spain, France, Austria and other countries.
The statistical offices of the European zone, Germany, the Czech Republic and some other European countries published their preliminary forecasts for economic development in the third quarter.
As expected, Germany's GDP grew by 0.5% and France's by 0.4%.
At the same time, both countries revised their data for the second quarter, in which Germany recorded higher growth than originally expected (growth of 0.3% instead of 0.1% forecast), while France admitted a slight decline of 0.1% (initial data only spoke of stagnation).
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent year-on-year in this year's third quarter.
Compared to the previous quarter, however, gross domestic product stagnated and, according to the Czech Statistical Office, the trend of slowing down in economic performance growth was confirmed.
The results are therefore worse than the analysts' forecasts.
The most important events:
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent year-on-year in this year's third quarter, but stagnated compared to the previous quarter.
According to preliminary and seasonally overcalculated data, the German economy grew by 0.5 percent in the third quarter.
Across the eurozone and the EU, the economy grew 0.2 percent between July and September compared to the previous quarter, in line with analysts' expectations.
The Greek economy shrank by 5.2 percent compared to the previous year.
The yield on its 10-year government bonds climbed to 28.45%.
The yields on Italian and Spanish government bonds rose to their critical limits.
Austria, the Netherlands, France, Belgium and other countries are also beginning to feel problems...
The yield on Czech government bonds remains below 4%, even as the situation in the region deteriorates.
In Germany, voices are being raised that the ECB should become the creditor of last resort.
