Iranian students are willing to die for their country's core program.
They formed a living shield.
Several hundred college students formed a living shield around a core object in Iran.
With this gesture, they wanted to demonstrate their support for their country's core program against a possible Israeli attack.
The students had prayed in front of the object on Tuesday noon and then announced death to the US and Israel.
A few hundred students from the university in Isfahan, Iran, formed a living sign around the nuclear technology center in Isfahan, where uranium is processed, on Tuesday.
They wanted to make it clear that they are prepared to protect their country's core programme, if necessary with their own lives.
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) recently stated in its report that Iran appears to have not given up its efforts to acquire a nuclear weapon.
Israel is also talking about a possible attack on Iranian nuclear facilities.
Students had prayed at noon in front of the entrance to the complex and then announced death to the US and Israel.
According to the Israeli press, in the event of an attack aimed at paralyzing Iran's nuclear program as far as possible, the nuclear enrichment facility in Natanz would also be targeted from the center in Isfahan.
The menu of an obese child: he does not eat breakfast and eats sausage for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with obesity, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys proved - obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important for the healthy development of a person is the environment in which he grows up and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more often on the table than in families in which normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had fries for dinner the day before the educational campaign under the motto "Obesity is no coincidence".
In families with fat children, sports are not exactly one of the favorite pastimes, but this also affects the majority of today's students - only 15 percent answered that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, during which almost 900 children from primary schools throughout the Czech Republic were interviewed.
This was already the second year of the campaign "Obesity is no coincidence", which is supported by the Allgemeine Krankenkasse and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grades have participated in the project.
Unhealthy food and lack of exercise in the family are decisive factors responsible for the alarmingly increasing number of children with overweight or even obesity.
"Only half of the children surveyed, for example, stated that eating breakfast five times a day in breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-vesper-dinner mode - one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet," according to one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relatively small things, such as the regular breakfast time of the family, are important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of students' families eat breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone has breakfast on their own.
Worst of all, one in ten families does not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
Among other things, the survey test revealed that families of overweight children consume unhealthy fries much more often.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet sodas every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed do sports, less than half of their parents do so - only 15 percent.
Create your own menu
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to put together their own meal plan according to their appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among her favorite foods were many pastries, meat dishes and, of course, desserts.
"The great popularity of sweet sodas is particularly alarming," the final report on this survey emphasizes.
At lunch, i.e. the main course, pasta won just ahead of poultry.
The children almost did not like legumes at all and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Return to health
At the same time, however, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they receive the right information.
"In the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after completing the educational presentation "Obesity is no coincidence", there was in many cases a clear shift in preferences towards principles of healthy eating," the results of the project state.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet sodas, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
The children also ticked poultry or fish as the main course of the day much more often in the questionnaire and were willing to eat fewer dumplings or sweet foods.
Professionals claim - a stylist must also be a good psychologist
In the introductory article about how stylists learn, I complained a bit that this was a bit too much stuff to start with.
I had no idea what was coming.
Lectures by three professionals from the industry, the clothing of problematic figures and a seminar on how it works "on the pitch".
Worse is set to come.
The closer the exam gets, the more information and practical tasks await us.
But even though the course takes place every Saturday and Sunday, it is still fully booked.
This time we debated with director Alena (not a single man participates in the course) how to dress a woman who does not have an ideally proportioned figure.
And that's what most of us are, after all.
Some have a too short neck, others a too boyish figure without proper curves and still others are chubby.
It is up to the stylist to visually conceal broad shoulders, lengthen the neck or conjure up the necessary curves.
We also got tips on how to dress a type of woman like Jennifer Lopez - with a big breast, wide hips and narrow waist - pretty and figure-hugging, without making her look too provocative.
If, for example, the difference between waist and hips is so big that the skirt or pants really do not fit, you should at least have a piece tailored to measure.
You will certainly not regret this, because well-fitting clothing is simply priceless.
In such a tailor-made skirt you feel much better than in one off the rack, which always slides up and down, sticks out at the waist, etc.
Boyish figures, on the other hand, can afford to wear clothing with pleats, puffs, appliqués, embroidery or gathers.
With so much information and character types, I'm glad that I have a whole week to think about everything thoroughly.
And yet I am afraid that it is almost impossible to do in view of the assigned homework.
Each of the course participants was assigned a celebrity for whom she should come up with suitable outfits - daywear and evening gown.
In doing so, we should take into account the current appearance, the fashion style of the corresponding star and his figure type.
I'm supposed to "attract" Miranda Kerr, whom you may know from the Victoria's Secret campaign.
Inside, I'm cheering, because that's much better for me personally than, for example, dressing Britney Spears or Christina Aguilera, who has probably gained a hundred kilos lately (well, that's a bit exaggerated), or even the young Selena Gomez.
We should cut out the garments from magazines or search the Internet, print them out and then edit them graphically.
In the "mood board", as the whole result is called, our very personal style and our relationship to graphic design should be expressed.
It is very important to also think about the graphic side of styling.
The stylist not only attracts the models purely physically, but also designs the so-called product page in the journals (according to specific specifications, for example trend handbags, coats, etc.).
Stylist and designer Mario Kameník told us about it.
But that only on Sunday.
This means that a stylist must have a good overall view.
The Saturday lecture, filled with information about figure types, was spiced up by three visitors from the industry:
by stylist Jan Pokorný, fashion designer Jakub Polanka and fashion photographer Ben Renč.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is illusion and that a stylist should be able to take advantage of it.
And a stylist sent in can work with a single garment in very different ways.
The magic word is variability.
For example, you can wear a trench coat over jeans as usual, like a T-shirt or coat, but you can also wear it on your naked body, put on heels and wear it as a dress.
It is enough to roll up the sleeves or the collar and the whole look looks completely different.
"Play with it," he stressed.
But the following advice came in handy for me the most: "First you have to know the rules perfectly."
"Only then can you hurt her," said Jakub.
Finally I realize why we have to cramming all these doctrines, what can be combined with what and why, even if you often get to see completely different things in fashion journals.
Not to mention fashion shows.
Thanks to photographer Ben, I now know that a stylist must have prepared many more clothing variants than he ultimately photographs.
So for a fashion story with ten pages (i.e. ten outfits) you have to be prepared to style at least fifteen.
And also that the clothing in the photo in combination with other accessories sometimes looks very different than in reality.
So you have to reckon with all this when designing the outfit.
Jan Pokorný also confirmed that image and style sometimes account for half of the success.
You only have to look at Madonna, a not exactly brilliant singer, from whom image and marketing have made a world star.
In the Czech Republic, the services of a stylist are rather reserved.
Even well-known personalities often consider this to be money thrown out (the main thing is that I bring something, how I look is secondary).
And if one of us can be styled, then we should expect that he or she will most likely force us a completely different (smaller) size than he or she really needs.
Then you only have to google to find out with certainty that the tabloid press writes that the corresponding celebrity has increased or decreased again, etc.
Jan and Mario advised us on Sunday not to believe that a stylist only needs to focus on fashion and then "assemble" the outfit.
In his work, he must above all communicate with the people he styles and he must be a shrewd psychologist.
Assess people without currying favor and standing by one's opinion.
"If some manager orders us to sift through her wardrobe and add pretty pieces, we can't clear out the whole closet and say - my God, that's terrible."
"You have to find at least a few commendable things to recommend what you can wear to," says Mario.
He also showed us very concretely what such a so-called "place bag" must contain.
So a bag that you button up at the waist and in which you carry all the necessary proprieties with you.
In addition to such clear things as scissors, dispensers for hair removal or safety pins, it also contains such utensils as a nylon thread (so that the stylist helps himself when photographing products, such as handbags or hats), special clips with which the clothes are gathered at the back if they are too big (pins or other clamps are prohibited so that the fabric does not break) and of course sewing kit.
So that we not only have to listen, but also have to try something practical, we learned how to glue shoes properly.
Even when photographing in the studio, where the floor is level, you can damage the sole of your shoe, let alone the one outside.
Us o glued and glued we...
You can't even touch the shoes with scissors, so you don't damage them.
So you have to be really clever.
Mario delighted me by praising my "creation" without reservation.
The dexterity mentioned is not exactly my strength.
All this was only a fraction of what we heard during the second weekend continuation course.
One thing has become clear to me by now - dedicating yourself to styling at a professional level is not child's play.
V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
A series of completely avoidable, amateurish mistakes turns the originally carefree journey into routine driving for the early shift.
It was possible to fulfil the ambitions to a large extent, but what good is that if obviously no one wanted to do a little more?
Even before it hit the counters, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" raised high expectations.
He promised to move the already old game series "Need for Speed" a bit into a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples he actually seemed to be not only one of many action racing games.
We were also curious to see how the fitted passages turn out, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you are used to with NFS, in the end a lot is different than you expected.
Sure - potentially they are quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is diminished by some superfluous bugs that have been present in this series more or less for a few years.
So these are actually no longer mistakes, but rather signs of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
First you are introduced to the story, whose main character Jack has certain problems of a personal character; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the West Coast, you get behind the wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a whole series of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
One does not have the impression for a moment that the game would offer the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are also very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing earth-shattering.
But the drive through the desert, through autumnal landscape or high up through a snow-covered landscape is visually very pleasant.
Every now and then, atypical elements bring a little variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, you are surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts the view.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be extremely careful not to be buried by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are installed quite well one after the other.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (basically a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then a personal duel with a single opponent awaits you.
And on top of that, the police get involved, who want to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
It's more about certain interactive animations in which Jack flees from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer such passages in the game than one would expect (specifically, probably only three).
Ultimately, this is rather to the advantage of the thing, because at least this element has no chance to get boring - in the context of the above, it is one of the elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today's point of view, it does not tear down trees, but on the other hand you could not say that it is bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But the local driving model continues to do justice to an action-packed racing quite well, although you could find better with the competition.
Until then, everything is fine.
Real problems only arise after a certain time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not quite OK.
It's hard to expect a game of this kind to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how the car behaves before hitting any object, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: When overtaking tightly or passing oncoming cars, you "touch" the other car only slightly in some places, but in other, almost identical situations you skid and do wild pirouettes.
Or drives the cart straight to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, this does not matter, but it is always annoying.
The restarts are solved like this: if you have a total loss or land far off the track, then the game throws you back to the last clue of the track.
Only - in each race you only have five restarts.
When you have exhausted them, everything starts all over again.
The restarts are therefore more like a tool, in case something does not succeed, but you should not rely on it.
Sometimes, however, not even the restart helps, nothing else helps than to learn the critical section from the head.
It is extremely unpleasant that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, you have to drive through some corners in a very specific way, otherwise you just can't fit through.
Elsewhere, you always encounter "civilian" cars in the same configuration at the appropriate point, regardless of whether you arrive first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see that the opponent in front of you passes two oncoming cars, but by the time you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around them or brake.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, everything is designed so that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The counterparties have even more advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent in the same place and again regardless of the timing.
This is craziest at the end of the game on the long bridge, which you pass in the opposite direction.
The opponent obviously has to overtake you here.
And if he is already in front of you, then of course he takes away your view, so that you drive your own car a few times in lumps at the beginning.
Sure - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly spoils the joy of the game.
And that's a pity, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining overall and sometimes so action-packed that you almost don't know where your head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what is "to blame" - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in such a way that boredom can not arise, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the car change in the course of the races.
You should not overlook the gas stations along the route, because just here you can change the car, although in most cases the car you have is sufficient.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for urban areas, the powerful American limousines for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical drives, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of the game story also goes the task mode (challenges) - ie the races in the individual localities, which you know from the story.
Here you can win not only medals, but also experience points for your own profile, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and the history.
In order to get to the higher driver level, various objects have to be unlocked: from the car to the background for the profile.
This is also linked to the online Autolog function, which, among other things, compares your own results with those of other players and also provides other collective functions.
One of other incomprehensible blunders is a situation in the last race in history.
Here you come by car into a subway tunnel (because of me), where you race in the dark on the rails (because of me).
On the speedometer there are numbers between 150 a 200 km/h (because of me), but suddenly a subway comes from behind and drives you uncompromisingly to scrap.
In our editorial team, we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is quite appealing in most cases and even brilliant here and there.
It is all the more annoying that in some exciting moments the refresh rate slows down and sometimes quite dramatically.
However, this applies in particular to accidents with a larger number of participants, where continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
The sound reproduction is OK so far and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to as broad a scale as possible to rather young audiences, a soundtrack a lá "something of everyone" was created - but who buys such a game because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
If the game hadn't been diminished by the totally unnecessary bugs mentioned, we could have said with the chest tone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that way the game seems kind of unfinished.
A great pleasure in itself, but you should be prepared for these mistakes to catch your eyes with the power of airport headlights.
Concert of the "Students of the Velvet Revolution" with vocal ensembles of Charles University
For the third time, the Festa Academica Festival offers the combination of World Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution and this including a musical experience.
In the course of the festival, about twenty professional and university choirs will introduce themselves.
The focus of the festival is on the two concerts, which will take place on 17 November.
"Charles University played a major role in the festival."
"Among the participants is the choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanistic Studies, and the Rector Václav Hampl sits on the festival committee," said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organizing team.
The absolute highlight of the festival is the public concert of professional school choirs, which will take place on 17 November from 2 pm on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
On the program is the composition of the important Czech jazz musician Karel Růžička "Celebration Jazz Mass".
In the evenings, the concert "Students of the Velvet Revolution" (Studenty sametu) takes place in the gala rooms of the People's House in Vinohrady, at which university choirs also perform, choirs of Charles University not excluded.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate World Student Day and commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music to the public at the highest level and to promote creative collaboration among young people.
The main organizer is the Association of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Johannes Kepler Gymnasium.
The entire event was sponsored by Bohuslav Svoboda, Mayor of the Capital City of Prague, and Václav Hampl, Rector of Charles University.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
In addition to festive concerts, the schedule also includes numerous music meetings, student happanings, matinees and other events.
Detailed information can be found on the website of the festival www.festaacademica.cz
EU Ambassador Vicenová:
The Czechs have a reputation as negativists and Eurosceptics
"The Treaty of Lisbon has noticeably upset the balance between the individual institutions."
I didn't expect such a hard war to break out."
"It will take five or six years for the waves to calm down and everyone to get used to their new role," Milena Vicenová, the Czech ambassador to the European Union, began her lecture at the Faculty of Law.
How seriously she takes the motto "Comprehensible and open about Europe" was already shown in the first part of her lecture, in which she succeeded in describing the individual institutions of the EU and their mutual relations in such a manageable and understandable way that many a lecturer at the Faculty of Law of Charles University could have envied her.
Ms Vicenová also praised the new permanent President of the Council of Europe, Herman Van Rompuy:
"Initially, there was criticism that he was too inconspicuous - a grey official who was not up to such a role, but I have to say it took everyone's breath away how well he took care of the matter.
"He is a person who manages to listen patiently to twenty-seven member states, to communicate with them and, above all, who has clear ideas about how to proceed with the EU.
She then explained the new position of the High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy as an answer to the question: Who is this - the European Union? Which number should I call?", i.e. as an important step towards unification and better readability of EU policy towards countries such as China or India.
Nobody wants to forbid us our oil mouc tvargels
Mrs Vicenová also addressed the agenda according to which the European Union has lived, is living and intends to live in the near future.
She described the Czech Presidency two years ago as a success.
The Czechs had mastered the financial crisis and the gas crisis and also organised the Eastern Partnership Summit.
She described the fall of the government during the Presidency as a major negative event that had seriously damaged the image of the Czech Republic.
The Czech representation in the EU currently has its hands full.
In the words of the Ambassador, not only the Presidency but also the subsequent crisis, which has not yet been overcome, was quite hectic.
And then the EU's seven-year budget has to be approved, which makes things much more complicated, precisely because of today's economic situation.
Whether it will be a lean and frugal budget, which sectors of the economy will be given priority, which countries will receive more and which will receive less support - all this is now on the agenda.
The ambassador also recalls her own slogans with which she came to Brussels: "Understandable about Europe".
"If there's something I don't like, it's greyish abbreviations, foreign words and jargon that nobody understands.
How am I, as a citizen, supposed to know whether Brussels is really coming up with crooked or round cucumbers and bananas of different sizes, or whether someone actually wants to ban us from using tvargel?
She would also have liked to use the soil of the EU to get more Czechs into European institutions.
Prospecting a two- or multi-speed Europe
According to the EU ambassador, the Czechs have a reputation for being Eurosceptics, who perceive the negative rather than the positive sides of the matter.
All the more annoying is the weak representation of Czechs in European institutions.
Many factors are to blame for this, including the reluctance of our candidates, their inability to write motivation letters and, last but not least, the weak support of the Czech side.
In addition to the successful Czech Presidency, she also highlighted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Group, the so-called V4.
"Believe me, when a Pole or Hungarian comes to me and a Slovak is nearby, the Frenchman next to me says: "Hey, what are you putting your heads together - is that your V4 again?"
According to Ms Vicenové, the EU expects tough rules for the budget policies of the member states in the future.
It sees the concept of a Europe of two or even different speeds as much more real than a "European federation".
"We have here the countries of the eurozone and the countries outside the eurozone.
"We have the Schengen area and we already have the Institute of Strengthened Cooperation."
"For the first time, it was said that only those countries that want it should work together and those that do not want it should stand quietly on the sidelines."
"There will be more and more such institutions, which will ultimately lead to a strong 'multi-speed Europe'," says Ms Vicenová.
In this regard, she also acknowledged the role of the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuyes in enforcing the principle that all issues affecting the EU as a whole must be discussed by all member states and not just by eurozone countries.
Brand Story:
The innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If you wanted to search for a suitable word that most accurately characterizes IBM's strategy, it would probably be the word "longevity".
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, known as a modern company, although a century has passed since its inception.
The foundation for this longevity was laid by its first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
He already advocated the slogan that countless global problems could be easily solved if people were willing to think a little.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the trademark around which the life of the future giant was to take place (and at the same time the title of the in-house magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
This was also the basis of Watsen's thoroughly prepared corporate culture.
"For us at IBM, this long-term thinking represents a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and succeeded for a century because it stayed true to its principles and didn't shy away from changing everything else around it.
This allowed us, over the course of our first century, to transform technologies, business and society.
We hope to achieve even more in the next hundred years," said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current director, on the occasion of the anniversary.
Well thought-out system
Watson already took social care of his employees in the thirties - in a similar way to the entrepreneur Baťa in Czechoslovakia: The IBM people were one of the first American employees to have paid holidays, insurance by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as work clothes and a well thought-out remuneration system for the best innovators and traders.
IBM's long-term relationships with its customers are just as sophisticated.
The company was brilliant in talent development right from the start - IBM was one of the first companies in the world to lift all discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
In line with this anti-discrimination strategy is also the current plan that Palmisan will be replaced at the helm of IBM next year by a woman - Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years, so far she has held the position of Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been doing so-called online brainstorming sessions, from which many future strategies and innovations will grow.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, the company employs almost half a million people.
An institution with a good reputation
Their unshakable position in the business guarantees the company a strong image both internally and externally.
"From the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company," said Harvard Business School professor and author of a book about IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
"IBM is not a technology company, it's a company that uses technology to solve business problems," added George Colony of consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company itself points out, there is a difference between just being present in the market or shaping it directly through that presence.
IBM - called "Big Blue" in the states because of its logo, has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It is one of the most versatile technology companies out there – IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services in an incredible range of products - from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all American technology companies, IBM owns the most patents and five of its employees have already been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His best-known inventions include ATMs, credit cards, financial swaps, barcodes and the floppy disk.
With a market capitalization of approximately $220 billion, IBM was the second-largest technology company this year (right after Apple), overtaking Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all products and innovations met the taste of today's customers - unfortunate were, for example, the attempt with the own operating system OS/2, the online service Prodigy or even the computers IBM PC jr.
"Business is based on forward movement, so you can't get emotionally attached to the past," says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That's why IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms – and if they don't work, leaving them.
In contrast to the opponent Microsoft, which in principle stands and falls with its operating system Windows.
Promising technologies
Services account for the largest share of IBM's profits, with software and hardware each accounting for one-fifth.
In 1990, hardware was still the most strongly represented with a share of more than fifty percent.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of low-profit assets, but in the same time it has invested $58 billion in purchasing promising technologies.
In these investments, IBM continues even after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world like a storm for the first time.
Again, IBM remained true to the legacy of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who increased his investment in the midst of the Great Depression.
So far, it seems that IBM is surviving today's crisis unscathed.
The value of IBM shares has skyrocketed by 120 percent since 2008, and the company's net profit is growing steadily.
IBM's corporate slogan is: everything can be changed - except the values.
This is another reason why it can be expected that this flexible giant will also master the next crisis.
IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flights
Founded a hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It did not adopt the name IBM until 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a subsidiary in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later company IBM was laid by the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They possessed technologies such as the famous time card clocks for registering the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the board of directors until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competing company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
This leader then eclipsed even the founders of IBM - Watson's ideas are still the basis of the company's invincible culture and identity.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the manufacture and distribution of all sorts of machines for the trade - from sausage and cheese cutters, to cash registers.
In the first four decades that Watson led the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the executive chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 60s, IBM technicians and computers helped NASA guide flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which determined the computer standard of that time, came in 1981 under the name IBM 5150 on the market.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand it bought the consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and thereby fully entered the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid off over the last three years is the "Smarter Planet" concept.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned before, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and city administration.
In the commerce sector, IBM recently launched the Smarter Commerce platform to help merchants manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932, IBM founded a subsidiary in what was then Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and is also home to a top world-class research team working on voice recognition technology.
