Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five approved state travel agencies in the then Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies mainly sold trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, at that time only select people were allowed to go to the West.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to Lake Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (including Czechoslovakians) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
If, for example, a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to accept huge queues or sleep in a sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, things had not gone for a long time.
The so-called foreign exchange promise - the condition for leaving for the West - was only granted to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange commitment it would have been impossible to raise the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The most Czechs spent their holidays inland, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dachas - a habit that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution by the Czechs.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries all over the world last year.
A huge paradox, of which one is no longer aware today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday destination of the Czechs - Croatia - until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation to the neighboring Western European countries was abolished, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
For a long time, Czechoslovakians simply could not get enough of their trips to the West, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
So the Czech tourists slept on trips to Paris in a tent in the park, because who would have had the money for accommodation in a hotel or in a guesthouse at that time.
A typical feature of trips abroad by Czechs at that time was a trunk packed with canned food, beer and sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech koruna - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and, as a result, average salaries increased, which in 1997 led to another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, after 1997 travel agencies began to regularly prepare trips through charter flights, which made air travel incredibly cheaper compared to the past thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts.
At the end of the 90s, the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, already had non-currency payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-velvet" travel occurred in 2000, when, thanks to high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was handled - Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying to distant sunny countries every year; This year, twelve exotic destinations will be served directly from the Czech Republic.
Around 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted visa requirements for Czech tourists, which definitely placed our country among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than CZK 15 thousand per capita on a single holiday stay, including costs at the resort.
The Annual General Meeting is to find a new chairman - again a stalemate threatens.
Czech football has not had a chairman for almost five months and there is a threat that Ivan Hašek's successor at the head of the Czech Football Association (FAČR) will not be known even after the extraordinary general meeting in Nymburk on Thursday.
To date, there has been no agreement on the electoral rules according to which elections should be held.
And without this, no vote on the three potential successors is possible at all.
Three interested parties want to manage Czech football - Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík.
In June, Hašek stepped down from his position, calling on his colleagues to come to an agreement and find a strong personality to lead football in the future.
Only - in the era after Hašek, the old quarrels broke out again between the two chambers of the association, which could not agree on a common candidate.
This was clearly demonstrated on 16 September, when the new chairman was to be chosen.
The delegates of the General Assembly had come to the People's House in Prague's Smíchov district for nothing, because the negotiations did not lead to any result and it was not only about the election itself.
It was not even possible to agree on who was actually entitled to vote in the full collection - only the statutory representatives or also the functionaries with a power of attorney.
At least partial agreement was reached on this single point, which was also supported by the recommendation of the Institute for State and Law, which considered that representation on the basis of power of attorney was not permissible.
However, disputes over electoral regulations continue.
Even the Executive Committee did not bring more clarity to the matter, at whose meetings - whether ordinary or extraordinary - in principle nothing else is on the agenda.
Even if the views regarding the election changed a few times, the neuralgic point remained the same.
The question is: how to proceed in the 3rd round to avoid a stalemate?
"The point of contention concerns the question of whether to proceed in accordance with the statutes, or whether a completely different model must be found," said Dušan Svoboda, one of the three vice-chairmen of FAČR, who represents professional football in management.
According to the statutory model, the winner in the third round is the candidate who receives the greater percentage of support in the chamber for which he is running.
Moravia is reportedly willing to accept the compromise that the candidate who receives the higher number of votes from both chambers wins.
The Czech side, on the other hand, insists on the condition that the winner receives at least a two-thirds majority in this percentage vote count.
"Then the two preliminary rounds no longer make any sense, this mode would call into question the entire bicameral concept," Svoboda understands the objections of the Moravian side, which would find it best not to bend the electoral regulations, but to vote according to the current statutes.
Surprisingly, Tomáš Paclík agrees, even if it becomes apparent that the statutory electoral rules of all candidates are most likely to suit Pelta.
"My wish is that elections will be held as far as possible according to the statutes."
"So that no nonsensical replacement variants are invented, as at the last general meeting," said the owner (of the football club) Victoria Plzeň, who is running for the first time and distinguished himself in his statements especially from Pelta.
But Pelta remains optimistic.
In his opinion, the new chairman will be known in Nymburk and he believes that the candidates will also cooperate constructively in the future.
"The possible qualification of the national team for the European Football Championship today would certainly help to calm the minds."
"If football is riding the euphoric wave, then the willingness to cooperate is greater," says the official from Jablonec, who has the most experience of all three adepts, both at professional and regional level.
Rajchl is more reserved.
"I hope for an agreement, but the situation is unfortunately ambivalent."
"This is not a matter between people from Bohemia and Moravia, but there are certain efforts to 'bend' the regulations for their own purposes."
"Therefore, a renewed blocking at the Annual General Meeting is not excluded."
"However, I hope that common sense ultimately prevails," Rajchl said.
Only - there is not much time left for all sides to agree.
Some negotiations were supposed to take place directly in Montenegro, but who knows if the football generality will even be complete by the time of the qualifying match.
The charter plane, with which Dalibor Kučera and Rajchl, among others, were to fly to Podgorice, could not take off in Prague in the morning due to a technical malfunction and so they feverishly searched for a replacement variant to bring part of the Executive Committee to the venue of the Barrage first leg.
In the end, the meeting at ministerial level, which is supposed to take place on Wednesday, is decisive.
Josef Dobeš, Minister of Education, Youth and Physical Education, would have liked to persuade the divided parties within the country's largest sports federation to reach an agreement.
There is a lot at stake: state subsidies, the trustworthiness of Czech football and also the upcoming general meeting of the ČSTV, which is intended to show Czech sport the new direction after Sazka's financial problems.
Paclík goes into battle for the position of chairman because he does not see a suitable candidate
If Tomáš Paclík, the head of the Pilsen footballers, had been able to identify a strong candidate before the extraordinary general meeting, who would have fulfilled all his ideas about the new chairman of the Football Association of the Czech Republic (FAČR), he would not have entered into the fight for this top position at all.
"If there was a good contender, I would fight for him and renounce the election."
"But in the current situation, it was not possible to find such an adept," said Paclík ČTK.
The main reason for Paclík to go into a duel with Miroslav Pelta and Jindřich Rajchl is therefore to prevent the alleged favorite of the election, Pelta, from reaching the top of the FAČR.
Paclík also emphasizes that in the event of his victory, he intends to exercise the function of Chairman for only one year, i.e. until 2013, until the date of the Annual General Meeting.
In the position of chairman, he would have liked to see an experienced top manager who is not too involved in football.
"I've spoken personally to some of the people in question."
"It's hard to believe that some people told me they didn't want to identify with Czech football at the moment.
"Such views would have liked to change," he said.
Most of all, Paclík is said to be bothered by Pelta's association with the chairman of the Pilsen District Football Association, Roman Berbr, a man with a controversial reputation who is considered a powerful lobbyist behind the scenes, with the ability to influence delegate votes at general meetings.
For Paclík, it is therefore unacceptable that Pelta would hold the position of chairman.
"If he wins, the current situation would be preserved and Czech football would not progress at all."
"The support of Berbr, a clever businessman, would be doubly bad for football," Paclík stressed.
He also alludes to the fact that Pelta's name was mentioned some time ago in connection with telephone tapping to investigate a corruption affair, from which Pelta emerged with impunity.
"I don't know what prestige a Pelta victory would bring to (Czech) football."
"And how would we look in the eyes of UEFA and FIFA," said řekl Paclík, who is a little more relaxed about his earlier statement that "he will sell the Pilsen football club if Pelta becomes chairman".
Should Paclík win in Thursday's election, however, he could imagine a future cooperation with Pelta.
Another candidate thinks the same way - Rajchl, whom Paclík had supported before the general meeting in October, which ended in a fiasco.
"He (Pelta) would be the first one I would go to."
"He has great abilities."
"I could well imagine him as head of the national team, for example."
"But I don't think he's capable of leading the association as a manager."
"I don't stick my nose into matters I don't understand about," said Paclík, who caused a stir in September by being behind the dismissal of the referees commission headed by Luďěk Macela, who was replaced by Dagmar Damková.
Paclík himself claims that he feels up to the role of association chairman.
Since last summer, he has also been head of Pilsen, which celebrated its first triumph in the league with his support in May.
"I have the power to change something in the football milieu and contribute to a certain cultivation of it."
"In order to limit the influence of certain interest groups that tend to influence disciplinary and appeal committees, which degenerates into repugnant situations," said Paclík, who makes no secret of his antipathy towards Sparta boss Daniel Křetínský, for example.
One of his priorities is to strengthen relations between the FAČR and the Czech Olympic Committee, with the help of which he would lobby political leaders for more money from the lottery tax to flow into sport.
"This is one of the crucial things that the new chairman should dedicate himself to."
"When it comes to the taxation of gambling, as the political parties declare, then I understand their reasoning, but then they must also say clearly where the money goes," he said.
Paclík also does not see his connection to the Pilsen club as a handicap, although he himself stresses that the chairman of the FAČR must be "non-partisan".
Pelta, in turn, is connected with Jablonec, Rajchl with the Prague Dukla.
"That's not ideal."
"In my opinion, however, it does not make much sense to hypocritically transfer my shares in the Pilsen club to a third person and to return after a year and a half," Paclík clarified.
Pelta promised new statutes of the FAČR, which would rule out a stalemate situation in the future.
Two days before the general meeting of the Football Association, one of the candidates for the chairmanship, Miroslav Pelta, promised that, if elected, he would campaign for the FAČR to get new statutes that would rule out disputes over the electoral regulations from the outset in the future.
The official from Jablonec is confident ahead of Thursday's hearing in Nymburk and believes that the election campaign will certainly defuse itself if the Czech selection is successful.
Pelta had already promised before the unrealized election in September that he would concentrate on the national team and the acquisition of funds if elected.
He decided only at the last moment to participate in the election before the last general meeting and so the two-month break may help him to defend his ideas about the management of football and to present them in a broader context.
"People at all levels are dedicated to football, they are impatient and therefore expect the chairman to be known on Thursday."
"He feels that it is high time that the federation is led by someone, says the man, who is mainly associated with the Jablonec club, but who also worked for many years at Sparta and on the executive committee.
This is another reason why he believes that he has sufficient experience to manage Czech football.
He is convinced that today's problems with the election are due to the euphoria that prevailed in the time of Ivan Hašek.
"Unfortunately, at the Annual General Meeting in June, articles of association were approved that were not as perfect as everyone had assumed.
If they hadn't allowed different interpretations, we would have had a chairman from September," Pelta said.
It was precisely the revision of the most important document of the civic association that he used as a lure for the delegates.
"If I become chairman, then I take care of it personally and am prepared to take personal responsibility if it does not work out."
"This is a matter of principle that he cannot be without," Pelta claims.
Furthermore, he does not try to distance himself from his opponents.
He had previously announced that he could imagine working with Jindřich Rajchl, whom he recognizes for his legal education, and he knows well that his opponent would be his first deputy.
He also did not attack Tomáš Paclík for a long time, who in turn did not leave a dry thread on Pelta.
He has been active in football for over a year and can already point to certain successes."
"However, his attacks were disparaging and many people were shocked by his campaign."
"This is another reason why many now doubt his real character," Pelta addressed his opponent, who would probably remain true to his proclamations, which he had already expressed in September.
In his opinion, his strongest weapon is the knowledge of football from the lowest divisions, up to the national team.
And this should be the figurehead of Czech football.
"I would also strive to end all affairs - from the Bohemian case to the reverberations of last year's corruption scandal."
