Europe's most beautiful pools
Jump into the blue
By Julia Stanek
Paddling pool in UFO look, state pools in Budapest: If you travel through Europe, you can experience its blue wonder - and after a city tour or a hike, rest your tired legs in bubble baths.
A book shows where wellness in the water is most beautiful.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip over the past year and a half, one thing could not be missing in her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying backwards on the water, she looked up into elaborately designed domes, swam towards marble putti waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming pools.
If she liked a bath, she quickly added it to her notebook - including interesting details about the construction and history of the building.
Architectural historian Meder explored more than 200 swimming pools in this way - and now presents them in her recently published book "Badefreuden": public swimming pools in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
Her "journey to the most extraordinary spas in Central Europe" took her through 13 countries: In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city each in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
She doesn't have much to do with sports, says Meder – only in the water it's different.
It's just annoying that swimming fans have to put up with blue tiles and chlorine stench, while joggers can breathe in the beguiling scent of spruce forests or listen to cheerful birdsong in the park.
"One day I asked myself why swimming pools always have to be so ugly," says Meder, who lives in Vienna.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Splashing in the diving pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all senses are served, according to Meder.
And if the builders have made an effort, swimming pools can be a real feast for the eyes: "Instead of a floor, you have a water surface in baths."
"On the one hand, it is transparent, but on the other hand, it reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, diving boards.
The small-format illustrated book "Badefreuden" conveys interesting facts about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases on 190 pages - but above all makes you want to jump into the blue.
The pool collector Meder discovered remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Bath in Budapest, she found nitrate-rich waters in a quaint karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a thermal bath whose pools are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
On the other hand, many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views: While you can see the whole city from the Zurich rooftop pool, you can look out over the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: In the steam bath there is a window from which you can watch the hustle and bustle on the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: The Aquadome Ötztal looks like a UFO that has just landed in the Alps.
In winter, it steams from three bowls open to the top, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal rise into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool, the smell of chlorine rose into the nose of the pool collector Meder.
Many thermal baths smell of sulphur, in the Árpád bath in Békescsaba, Hungary, it stinks so much of heating oil that you hardly believe you have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali-hydrogen carbonate-containing healing water, which is almost black and whose silt sticks to your skin as soon as you slide into the pool - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing areas: When she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing in the Czech bath Luhatschowitz, she found a cordoned-off terrain.
The bath, designed in 1902 by architect Dušan Jurkovic, has since been closed.
When Meder took a look through the weathered windows of the red, white and yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
On the other hand, the decay was counteracted in an enchanting swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
This bath has already completed three construction phases; You can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements dating back to the time of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, added around 1900.
Since its careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favorite bath of pool expert Iris Meder - and not only because she originally comes from the Black Forest.
"It's quite an achievement to merge such different architectural styles into such a great unit," says Meder.
With such a palace, the dive in the thermal pool is apparently only a minor matter.
Agricultural speculation
Deutsche Bank sheds light on commodities business
By Christian Teevs
Is Deutsche Bank going out of its agricultural commodities business?
According to SPIEGEL ONLINE information, Josef Ackermann has commissioned a working group to examine the consequences of speculation for the world's poor.
In January, the CEO wants to draw consequences.
Hamburg-
For German citizens, the matter is clear: According to a study, 84 percent of Germans find it unacceptable for banks to speculate with agricultural commodities such as wheat or corn.
Two-thirds of respondents even demand that Deutsche Bank and other credit institutions get out of this business because it exacerbates the problems of the world's poorest.
This is the result of a Forsa survey commissioned by the consumer organisation Foodwatch.
The study is based on a report presented by Foodwatch in mid-October.
In it, the author Harald Schumann shows that the bets on the global commodity exchanges drive up prices - and the banks are therefore partly to blame for the worldwide hunger problem.
The campaign of the consumer advocates is specifically directed against Deutsche Bank boss Josef Ackermann, even if major banks such as Goldman Sachs or Morgan Stanley act similarly.
Originally, commodity bets were intended to hedge traders against price fluctuations.
But now most experts agree that the gamblers have decoupled from supply and demand - and make profits at the expense of the poorest.
Unlike U.S. competitors, Ackermann responded to the criticism, promising to investigate the allegations and saying no deal was "worth risking Deutsche Bank's reputation."
According to information from SPIEGEL ONLINE, an international working group is currently examining the allegations from the Foodwatch report.
The audit is expected to be completed by the end of the year, when the results will be presented to Deutsche Bank's Management Board - including a recommendation on how to deal with them.
At the end of January, the top of the bank wants to announce what consequences it draws.
The end result could be a reduction in the raw materials business, or even a complete abandonment.
Ackermann tinkers with his image
Foodwatch boss Thilo Bode welcomed the news, but at the same time reiterated his criticism of the financial sector: "Betting on rising food prices shows particularly drastically how ruthlessly banks are harming the common good today."
As the top bank lobbyist, Ackermann is now particularly responsible.
"Deutsche Bank must remove from its portfolio all investments where money is used to bet on food prices," Bode said.
"No matter whether Mr. Ackermann is concerned with people suffering from hunger or the reputation of Deutsche Bank."
Ackermann's insight comes as a surprise at first glance, but it is clear that the CEO wants to give a perfect picture a few months before leaving office.
On Monday, Deutsche Bank announced that, unlike planned, the CEO will not move to the supervisory board.
By turning away from controversial agricultural speculation, he could improve his image.
And he hardly needs to worry about possible losses - after all, his successor would have to do with that.
One in two would cancel commodity investments
Foodwatch strives to keep the pressure on the manager high.
So far, more than 30,000 internet users have participated in the organization's campaign.
On Tuesday, Bode published the survey, for which the Forsa Institute interviewed 1,001 people on November 7 and 8.
Only eleven percent consider it legitimate for Deutsche Bank to offer investments that bet on prices for food.
Many bank customers would also draw personal consequences if they learned that their bank participates in such transactions: According to the survey, one in two would cancel all investments in which money flows into commodity speculation.
43 percent would advise acquaintances against such a bank, 49 percent said they were thinking about terminating their account and switching to another institution.
21er Haus in Vienna
The relocated pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy endings: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion in Brussels in 1958 won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and fell into disrepair.
Now it is being reopened as an exhibition venue.
If people rave about modern post-war architecture, clear forms, glass halls, bold curves and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion by architect Karl Schwanzer for the Brussels World Exhibition in 1958 is a striking and famous example.
At the time, Schwanzer's pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still regarded as a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built pavilions at Austria's next World Exhibition.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like annex in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion, planned as a temporary exhibition building, was set up after the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden near Vienna's Südbahnhof, rebuilt and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century was opened in it - it was called the "20er Haus".
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art got a new house in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building stood empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used as a museum for contemporary art in the future.
On Tuesday evening, the Museum Belvedere, to which the museum belongs, opens its first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every respect.
The new beginning was achieved by Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, who holds a doctorate in art history with a remarkable career, including in her youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, emphatically pushed through the conversion with politicians and preservationists, she procured public funds and private sponsorship money and determined its use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there was to be a café and a bookshop, and an office building had to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krischanitz was the ideal choice for the implementation.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzer at the Vienna University of Technology and the pavilion was a "tremendously important place" for him, where he had seen the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost its generosity and lightness when it was transferred to Vienna and converted.
There were far bigger problems with the current conversion: The building was "an energy guzzler," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass façade were replaced, glass-fibre-reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel girders have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been renovated.
Two basements provided space for the new use, a lowered light trench between the house and the street provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old reddish-brown rust protection color.
And the cinema hall is even exactly as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also appealed to the monument protection office," says Krischanitz and points to a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and conversions, the building has remained flexible and light.
It was difficult with the pavilion, "which came from Brussels," Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story."
Such architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken a real awareness".
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because an urban planning stroke of luck has occurred: Around the Swiss Garden, the completely newly planned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier", with office and residential buildings, is currently being built.
And another stroke of luck may still occur: The 21er Haus could be strengthened by another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berlin Temporäre Kunsthalle, and as one hears, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighborly location in the Swiss Garden.
Deutsche Bahn plans winter crisis package worth millions
