The bank did not admit any guilt with the settlement.
This also applies to Citigroup, which committed to pay $20.5 million.
NCUA Chairwoman Debbie Matz welcomed the concessions of the two financial institutions.
The National Credit Union Administration (NCUA) is responsible for the US credit unions and steps in in the event of bankruptcies to protect customer deposits.
The NCUA is trying to get the billions of dollars in damage compensated.
The settlements now concluded are the first of their kind.
The regulator had also taken on other major banks and sued JPMorgan Chase, the Royal Bank of Scotland and Goldman Sachs in the summer.
The mortgage securities in question are so-called mortgage-backed securities.
These are based on home loans.
When the US housing bubble burst in 2007, this was the downfall of a large number of financial firms.
In September 2008, at the height of the financial crisis, the US investment bank Lehman Brothers tipped over.
Even though the events took place several years ago, a sharp wind is currently blowing against the banks in the USA.
Investors and regulators have filed countless lawsuits seeking redress or misconduct.
