The scandalous bank of Lake Zurich
The most adventurous bank in Europe is not located in Italy or France, but in Switzerland.
UBS almost went bankrupt during the financial crisis and has been sliding from one crisis to the next ever since.
Now a German is to judge it.
Axel Weber certainly didn't think so.
After his spectacular departure from the top of the Bundesbank, it was announced in July that he would take up an almost equally spectacular new job in 2013: Chairman of the Board of Directors of the major Swiss bank UBS - an unexpected and lucrative career move.
Axel Weber was publicly pleased, praised Switzerland for its beauty and UBS for its newfound solidity and made friendly remarks about his future colleagues.
"UBS has achieved the turnaround."
"I am looking forward to working with Kaspar Villiger and Oswald Grübel".
But already in September it became clear that everything would turn out quite differently.
A trader of UBS in London had bypassed all protection systems of the bank and gambled away around 1.7 billion euros.
UBS CEO Oswald Grübel, a banker who is not only famous in Switzerland, had to go.
Since then, the Chairman of the Board of Directors of UBS has also been regarded as ailing - and everyone is asking: When will Axel Weber finally arrive?
It has already been announced that Weber will be allowed to advise the bank from February 2012.
And he will take over the chairmanship of the board of directors in May - not just in 2013, as the bank announced on Tuesday.
This will be tough for Axel Weber.
He is not a banker, but rather an economics professor and central banker and would certainly have needed a training period.
All of a sudden, he takes responsibility for the strategy of a bank that has just proven once again that it has long since earned the title of "Europe's largest scandal bank".
On the one hand, UBS is huge - until recently it was the largest asset manager in the world - and on the other hand, it has been sliding from one scandal to the next for years.
Nothing, it seems, is spared the once so proud Swiss bank.
It started in the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
She had combined the image of the secretive and solid, but also clever Swiss asset manager with ambitious goals: she also wanted to become a big name in investment banking.
In 2007, UBS managed $1.6 trillion, more wealthy clients than any other bank in the world.
And on the other hand, as an investment bank, it had moved into the league of the largest banks in the world.
That made an impression.
Hans Geiger, a former banker and later a long-time banking professor in Zurich, explains: "Back then, I always presented UBS to my students as a model of a good bank."
"From today's point of view, one wonders: How could I be so wrong?"
He was terribly mistaken.
In 2007, it became apparent for the first time that something was going seriously wrong at UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli, who until then had been regarded as a highly intellectual and equally ingenious banker, surprisingly resigned.
A few months later, one could guess why he had left.
The investment division of the bank had gambled away with subprime securities and had to write off billions.
To shoulder this, UBS announced a capital increase of no less than 13 billion Swiss francs.
But she actually found investors, but some that some would have turned up their noses at until recently: a non-transparent Asian sovereign wealth fund from Singapore and an Arab sovereign wealth fund that was so secretive that one did not even learn its name.
But that was only the first blow.
Things got worse in April 2008.
The bank had to announce new billions in losses, Chairman of the Board of Directors Marcel Ospel, in 2006 still the second-best-paid Board of Directors in Switzerland, resigned.
In October 2008, disaster followed: UBS was on the verge of collapse due to its bad investments in the financial crisis and had to be rescued by the state.
The SNB bought from UBS for tens of billions of problematic securities, while the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for a forced convertible bond, through which it could become co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shocked - because she noticed how dramatic it is for a small country to host such large banks.
After all, UBS's total assets in 2007 were more than five times as large as Switzerland's economic output (see chart).
"Once again, we could not save UBS," says banking researcher Geiger.
The first catastrophe was followed by the second.
Just a few months later, UBS capitulated in the tax dispute with America and agreed to hand over the data of wealthy clients who had possibly evaded taxes with the help of the bank.
In addition, it agreed to a payment of 780 million dollars - as a repayment of unjustified profits from these transactions, including a penalty.
UBS thus more or less openly admitted that it had helped with tax evasion.
At the same time, it lost something that had always been its capital in the competition for rich customers: the aura of secrecy.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was no longer the same.
This was followed by the resignation of the Chairman of the Board of Management and the Chairman of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of client funds.
Within a few months, the bank had lost its credibility in both central business areas: in investment banking through the erroneous speculation and in asset management through the help of tax evasion.
And just when it calmed down a bit, just when you thought UBS would get it done again, there follows this unfortunate trader story: A single trader gambles away 1.7 billion euros before the bank realizes that something is going wrong.
And it becomes apparent: Risk management in investment banking is obviously still not working.
"With the Adoboli case, we have seen that too little has changed in risk control," says Martin Janssen, economist and finance professor at the Banking Institute of the University of Zurich.
The CFO of a large German bank is also certain: "UBS's problem is that it does not have risk control under control."
Yet it had been precisely the idea of caution with which the Swiss bankers had long ago set out to become guardians of the world's great fortunes: not too big risks, but security for money - even if the world might collapse beyond the Alpine republic.
The vaults of Swiss banks had become a symbol of unshakable reliability, just as Lindt and Sprüngli had become for particularly fine chocolate.
The headquarters of UBS in Zurich still fits the cliché of the dignified Swiss private bank - it is just a little bigger.
Even the location is classic.
The bank has its headquarters on Zurich's Bahnhofstrasse, which leads from the main station directly to Lake Zurich, which is framed by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are magnificent, the shop rents are among the highest in Europe.
Jewellers like Tiffany's can be found here between traditional Swiss shops such as Confiserie Sprüngli.
Swiss banks have resided here for centuries: from the National Bank to the Palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Baer.
You enter the UBS reception hall through a heavy revolving door.
Inside, the walls are covered in marble, in front of them are thick leather armchairs, next to the bank logo a large sign to the "safe".
UBS knows what its client is looking for: security.
However, both major Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, have at some point suppressed this idea of the Swiss bank - or betrayed it, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper, after all, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with the two big banks.
UBS has become far too big, he thinks – especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons have also spread.
The Swiss would have nothing more to say there.
"And if they do, they have long since adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons."
In fact, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, first brought it high profits and then the debacle: No European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the major Swiss bank.
On October 15, 2008, the catastrophe became visible.
"On that Wednesday, the governing coalition of the small country of seven million decided on the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation," writes author Lukas Hässig in his book "The UBS Crash".
The politicians approved up to 68 billion Swiss francs or around 45 billion euros to save the major bank, which was facing bankruptcy.
How did this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem mainly in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks merged to form a huge group.
The result was a bank that was already too big for small Switzerland at the time of the merger - and continued to grow.
It helped that the two different predecessor banks of UBS complemented each other: a rich but sleepy bank with a focus on asset management in Zurich and a poorer, but already more internationalized one.
Suddenly, the internationalized investment bankers got a lot of cheap money with which they could turn a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
"I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team," says banking researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the highly intellectual, modest man who understands a lot about models and statistics, and Ospel, the gut man who has worked his way up from banking apprenticeship to the very top."
But Ospel relied on Wuffli in the end.
And Wuffli probably made a decisive mistake in the end: "He thought his models were reality," says Geiger.
"This is a tragic case."
Tragic, perhaps.
One thing is clear: exuberance came before the fall.
UBS employees clearly remember the executive meetings at which CEO Wuffli repeatedly issued the same slogan: Dethrone Goldman Sachs.
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank on earth.
She led the "League Tables", the rankings that documented the success of the banks of the time.
That's where UBS wanted to go to the top.
She had already succeeded in taking a few steps.
In the foreign exchange business and in stock trading, she played at the top.
Management consultants who were commissioned, however, highlighted a weakness: In the international interest business, in the banker's language "fixed income", there is a huge gap to the largest banks.
UBS has gaps in American mortgage products.
To fill this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that almost cost them their existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a hedge fund founded before it invested in American subprime assets.
It developed into a formidable machine that packaged and passed on securities on American mortgage loans - but also retained risks itself.
Even when other banks had long been looking for an exit.
"In the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was in flames, UBS bought there," says banking expert Geiger.
As great as the euphoria, so deep is the fall.
One manager after another had to leave when the attempts to clean up turned out to be more difficult than expected.
Posts at UBS became an ejection seat and are still shaky today.
Whoever leads the big bank now has an almost impossible job.
He has to find a strategy for a bank that has lost all obvious business models.
Banking researcher Geiger already has an idea: end investment banking, concentrate on asset management, return to Swiss roots.
The bank does not (yet) want to go quite that far.
But investment banking is to shrink sharply, that much is already clear.
Next Thursday, the new bank boss Sergio Ermotti wants to present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Italo-Swiss was actually only intended as a temporary solution when the bank surprisingly parted ways with predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has prevailed: He should permanently lead the business of UBS, said the Zurich bank on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants to reduce the investment bank to the level of the mid-nineties.
He cuts 3500 jobs.
But that won't be enough.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
How does she want to earn money?
These are the questions Axel Weber is certainly already asking himself.
So far, he has only said publicly that he and his wife will first look for an apartment in Zurich.
Next year.
