Smart crows spread in cities
In many places, rooks are considered "problem birds": But experts claim that the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of the cities.
Some like them, others want to get rid of them very quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities residents complain about the dirt and noise of the animals are piling up.
A remedy against the "problem birds" is not yet in sight.
Seed crows are no longer to get out of the cities, said experts at the first crow symposium in the East Frisian Leer.
There, experts from all over Germany discussed possible ways out.
You are looking for alternatives in the cities
Conservationists also attributed the problems in cities to the rural exodus of specially protected rooks: The use of chemicals in agriculture is increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
Hunting, increasing development and the felling of typical breeding trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs exist in Soest in Westphalia, in the northwest in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen as well as in Leer.
There, in 2005, a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the district had made negative headlines.
Critics had described the capture of the animals in bird traps and the killing with clubs as particularly brutal.
"The normal expulsion, the scaring, brings nothing," said the urban and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer.
Spraying away nests with water or felling trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals dodge, large colonies split up and spread elsewhere."
Deterrence is only conceivable as an exception at hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
"We have to live with them, we can't get them away."
Without the surrounding area, the problem in the cities could not be solved, said Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
A combination of scaring off the animals from sensitive living areas and bait offers is conceivable in order to resettle them in other places.
"Information boards instead of chainsaws", on the other hand, promoted psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens for a completely different approach to animals: "After all, we can best bear a pimple on our face with confidence."
Jürgens had co-founded the Ascheberger Krähen-Lehrpfad in Schleswig-Holstein, where information signs provide information about the life of highly intelligent rooks.
The project has already been accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on the criticism of the noise of the birds: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say to each other."
The intelligence and dexterity of the animals are legendary: rooks not only use tools to get a treat, but even make their own tools as aids.
Behavioural scientists at the University of Cambridge recently tested how far the birds' intelligence reaches on four rooks.
