He has written an unusual book, which he describes not inaccurately as "a work of anti-history".
It contains few big names, important treaties or famous battles. There are hardly any ambassadors, frenzied reporters or discussions about tactics and equipment.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, but rather "a book about what it was like." It is about "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Terror" almost the war experiences of 20 more or less inconspicuous men and women on both sides of the war combined, from schoolgirls and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and office workers.
Some of these people become heroes.
Some become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go crazy or die.
Each of these lives flickers like the votive candles in a church, some are added while others go out.
Englund's book deviates from the usual history books.
It also corrects the notion that World War I was merely the devastating trench warfare on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Terror" wanders with an expert's eye over other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Beehives fall on the soldiers in this book, one celebrates Christmas under the pyramids in Egypt, tsetse flies are an unsolvable problem.
This is a moving book almost from the beginning.
War is flooding the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina that smells of cordite.
Imagine you are a woman who is at home with her children and hears cannon fire in the distance. Do you stay or do you flee?
Who is coming?
Hardly anyone understands what is happening or why this war is being waged at all.
"Missing facts," Englund notes, "have been brushed up with assumptions, assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"Beauty and Terror" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young German ship's sailor.
Their stories were mainly taken from memories, letters and other material already published.
Their life stories can be frightening or poignant, but they are extremely vivid in Englund's collection of small moments that lose in details.
