"Spare coffee, fake aluminum, wrong eraser, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He tells us more about substitute food in Germany.
He describes "meat made from pressed rice and baked in mutton fat (and last served with a false bone of wood), tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato peels, shoes soled with wood."
There were, as he notes, "837 registered food substitutes allowed in the production of sausages, 511 registered coffee substitutes."
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
An American recognizes his own urge for savagery and says of the war: "One feels that, despite everything, this is what was intended for men rather than sitting in an armchair, with the evening paper or the bestseller and a cigarette and a whiskey in one's hand, and pretending that such a façade means civilization and as if there is no barbarism behind one's starched and fogged shirt breast."
