Instead, it's as horrible as "a condemned man hanged in secret."
Other observations are about old Europe falling apart and new forms of terror.
"The conflict increasingly became an economic contest," writes Englund, "a war between the factories."
He captures the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the bestiary of the still young century": "the eloquent and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a tailor-made suit who slaughters while sitting behind a desk."
People behave in unforeseen ways and there is just as frivolous behavior as heroism.
Englund discusses the soldiers who actively tried to catch a venereal disease from a prostitute in order to escape frontline service.
