The bill was rejected in the Senate by a broad fringe group of both parties and there was no vote.
But on the same day, this bill failed in the Senate. In addition, the chamber overruled a decision to cut funding for American operations in Libya.
This put the US mission in a kind of legislative purgatory, with a Congress that was outraged enough to criticize Obama's actions on the mission, but not angry enough to pull the rug out from under his feet once and for all.
Then Congressional indecision was overtaken by events.
Tripoli fell under Libyan rebels in August and Gaddafi was killed on October 20.
The NATO mission officially ended on October 31.
Now the Senate may be ready to act.
The resolution of the Committee on International Relations "congratulates the people of Libya on their tremendous courage and extraordinary perseverance in their self-liberation" and "commends the men and women of the U.S. military and their coalition partners who support military operations to protect the people of Libya for their extraordinary courage and professionalism."
