Goodlatte's amendment is just one of 68 constitutional amendments presented to this Congress that cover a wide range of issues.
Some are double—the same bill has been submitted to both Congress and the Senate—others differ only slightly.
There are at least 15 versions of the balancing budget amendment in the Senate alone, and another dozen that would "control federal spending."
Some of the laws are also identical, but they give their principals — especially Republican beginners who want to polish up their resumes — the opportunity to brag that they "wrote" such a measure.
The Budgetary Control Act, passed in August, requires both the Senate and Congress to vote on a change to the balancing of the budget.
