Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who broadcast their anti-immigration opinions online.
On Monday, Breivik, who has confessed to committing crimes in a July shooting spree in Norway that killed 77 people, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he spent much of his time in front of his computer before his attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social media.
After this summer's tragedy, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It's easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
"We found that it wasn't hard to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British think tank DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook's hiding place for personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply have to use the site's advertising tool to pinpoint their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy — just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with Adds, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the Adds invited users to a survey asking about their level of education, attitudes toward violence, and their assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries — without even having to leave their offices.
"It's a fairly new research method," Bartlett says.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online promoters of far-right groups are mostly young, male, and annoyed by immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more sensible, democratic, and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens."
DEMO's work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends like in "likes," text messages, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating a research boom that has increased the number of scientific papers with this page's name in the title by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that through this page you can study people you normally can't reach with your clipboard on the street.
"In the past, if you tried to interview people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"They had to inform the party first, and they would never have allowed them access," Bartlett says.
"With Facebook, that's all gone — you go straight to them."
Others say the site provides a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their intoxication on Facebook were significantly more likely to drink problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that peer students, such as housing counselors, monitor the site and help a student if it posts too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you haven't recognized it," Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of child health, behavior and development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, told The Washington Post.
"We found a way to identify vulnerable children who would not have been found otherwise."
Facebook is also constantly tapping into the data of its own population.
The site's data team compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (primarily using information that only Facebook has access to — masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its vast treasure trove of data available to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not. In order to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, you allow the site to share your personal information.
But what if Facebook's users become part of a survey they don't even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how they collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
"I don't think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles," Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, says of a 2006 study in which he examined students' public pages on Facebook.
"As for her, it was all about her and her friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant will be completely honest.
On Facebook, it's impossible to know how much of the information in a user's profile and posts is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things," Selwyn says.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
"There's no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people," he says.
"Social research has to take care of the social – and a lot of social life still takes place offline."
