7 lessons from the interview with the late Steve Jobs shown in a theater this week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting the technical genius as a great modern inventor.
But perhaps what Apple fans find most revealing in the recently rediscovered Jobs interview, which was dusted off this week ahead of special screenings in major markets, is how much this creative mind understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and a self-proclaimed hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer eagerly tinkering with diagrams—a man who believed that many business leaders suffer from "a disease of thinking that a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work... [but] there's an enormous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph der Fachidioten" about the advent of the personal computer. And he sat with Jobs for more than an hour, during which they had one of the rare, in-depth conversations.
At that point, more than 10 years had passed since Jobs had been pushed out of Apple. And he was already working his new computer company, NeXT, and was looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley's interview was used in professional idiots, he says the interview's copy templates were missing on delivery.
It was only after Jobs' death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the principal's garage.
This slightly revised footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which comes to the Landmark theatres this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for loathing in-depth interviews, Jobs here appears surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In the course of the interview, there are four longer pauses between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of contemplation, in which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism comes to light when he seems impatient to Cringely's questions and pushes him to respond more quickly to topics or subplots of greater importance.
Recorded before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, the Lost Interview seems somehow incredibly far-sighted when Jobs evaluates what he thinks other companies are doing right or wrong and represents his own vision for the future of the computer.
It's one thing to read posthumous tributes to Jobs' career. But seeing Jobs here as the eager dreamer on the verge of greatness is something quite different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could and should be.
Shortly after he had done all this, he went and did it.
A quick look at seven notable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a business:
"Throughout all the years in business, I always ask, 'Why do you do things?' And the answer you always get is, "Oh, that's just how it's done."
No one knows why he does what he does. No one in the business really thinks deeply about things.
That's what I've noticed.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Stunned at how costs were recorded—usually starting with "standard costs" that were quantified on mere guesswork and then adjusted with "deviation"—he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined down to the smallest detail.
How the Pope was ridiculed:
Jobs talks about the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed you to sneak into the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Jobs' enthusiasm when he describes the blue box as an act of self-empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak would test the box by using a toll phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while looping through as many satellites as possible.
"We sent things around the globe half a dozen times and if you yelled into the phone, it came out a minute later on the phone next door," Jobs says with a chuckle.
"We were young and we learned that we could build something ourselves that could control trillions of dollars of infrastructure around the world."
Both of us, we didn't know much, but we were able to build this little thing that can control a gigantic thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don't think Apple would exist without them.
Jobs goes on to tell of a glorious prank that Wozniak and he almost pulled off when they called the Vatican in the middle of the night via Blue Box and wanted to talk to the Pope, while imitating Henry Kissinger as best they could.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the Pope himself got on the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and called Bill Hewlett unprepared):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs landed a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
"That had a remarkable impact on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views of what a company was and how well it treated its employees."
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made."
It was the size of a suitcase, had a small screen with a Braun tube and I fell in love with it.
I would climb to the top of HP as a teenager and hang on to this machine and write programs for it.
How to improve innovation:
Several times in the interview, Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he was installing some circuit boards, he was asked by a customer to assemble the entire computer.
He worked with a payment deadline of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple, he recalls the problems he had developing a computer mouse:
"I remember resounding arguments... They yelled at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could have built for $15. That was incredibly credible.
On large companies that are declining:
Long before he revived Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled with their visions and lost control of their shares.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make a better copier or printer, so what?"
They have the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [it's people like that] who ultimately run the companies and the product that pushes people out of decision-making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is being eradicated by the people who have no concept of good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship necessary.
This is what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
You could have been ten times bigger if it had been Microsoft in the 1990s...
They have caught the defeat from victory.
About innovation as an art form:
"There's a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop this great idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
You have to make votes, certain things you can't do, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5000 things, these concepts, and bring them all together...
At the end of the day, it boils down to taste, it boils down to trying to deal with the best stuff that humans have created, and then trying to bring those things together into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who worked there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happen to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for the computer industry, they would be doing fantastic things in other areas.
