How to expose a lie
A look at the current headlines shows how alarming and widespread deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy dealing with allegations of sexual harassment by several women. Both sides accuse each other of lying.
Penn State management is accused of perjury for allegedly withholding reports that a retired football coach sexually abused boys.
Last week, French President Nikolas Sarkozy told US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar over an open microphone.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were quickly refuted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton unleashed when he lied about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in the Oval Office.
Stories about cheating at school and college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents where teachers have given their students the exam answers so that they themselves did well in their performance reviews.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lying and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
As studies show, we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
However, many of these lies are considered white lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing lies or "exposing lies" is one that is important for every person to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a parlour game such as charades, in which the goal is to shout "Get you!", debunking a deception is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have conducted wide-ranging research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Lies look you in the eye.
They stutter, stammer, blush and do not always fidget.
However, one must not conclude from this that these liars are difficult to uncover and expose.
A skilled liar can get through to the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, questioning and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific findings of the vast and ever-growing field of exposure. And it is clear that debunking deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us navigate our complex world, especially when hiring or questioning people or negotiating or administration are part of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at assessing other people, arousing their interest and controlling their own emotions. And they intuitively sense how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men are more likely to tell "self-oriented" lies than women whose lies are more "oriented towards others" – usually trying to protect the feelings of others – that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly "fat lies").
We also know that when a person has been exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty for lying to that person.
How do you tell if someone is lying?
First, by observing that person's normal behavior.
This is called "baselining", the starting position.
It provides a reference point for later evaluation of changes.
Observe the posture, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
They should better know when someone usually trips with their foot all the time, so they don't wrongly blame them when they trip with their foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Think of these accumulations as alarm bells ringing, not evidence of exposure.
People who deceive may freeze when they try to remember their history. Maybe their feet point toward the door, or they lean toward the exit, change their position in significant ways, or show a "post-interview relaxation," that deep, relaxing exhalation, and change in posture when all the hard questions are over.
Questioners often mistakenly signal that an interview is over, only to look for that relaxation after the interview.
Also pay attention to the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson's slip-up is famous when he used the past tense when he claimed his slain wife was still alive and sparked a national search for her.
Deceptive people may also use distancing language: "I didn't have a sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question as a whole.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when answering a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth... As far as I know... to the best of our knowledge and belief."
This makes the answer more perceptive than factual, which often rings alarm bells.
There is no magic bullet for exposing lies, but you can learn skills that make exposure possible.
Thanks to these skills, anyone is less likely to become a victim of fraudsters, both in private and professional life.
