Climatic adversity slowed down the economy
In the first year that Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and undeclared work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in Sinaloa's economic history. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of change and raised great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, as a result of climatic adversities, there can be no question of growth; on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses in the millions of dollars in agriculture, but also placed tight limits on the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter, mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which had a dampening effect on other sectors of the economy.
According to a report on the effects of the frost issued by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582,000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent partially destroyed. Vegetable, maize and chickpea crops were particularly affected.
The decline in economic activity until November has caused unemployment to rise steadily in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, because from January to March, 55,053 inhabitants of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74,000 unemployed in Sinaloa. This is 18,969 more people than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa that year is due to several factors. The economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences at the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments that the policies of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment that has to do with several factors. Among other things, with liquidity losses in the market as a result of funding cuts by legislation passed in Congress to combat money laundering, because it is not easy for those who illegally accumulate dollars to make them work for them, to invest them or to use them for anything else," he explained.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that there is also a demographic factor inherent in growing unemployment.
"The number of people leaving the country in search of work abroad, particularly in the United States, has decreased. This is due on the one hand to the entry problems and on the other hand because it is difficult to find work there as well. These people stay here and look for work here, which increases unemployment," he says.
Moonlighting
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious when one takes into account the high proportion of undeclared work. According to INEGI, this includes 60.38 percent of employees in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
In addition to unemployment and undeclared work, there are low wages, the lowest in Mexico, according to statistics from the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institution) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Agency for Labor and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos until September; this is much less than the national average, which is 7375 pesos.
Decline in FDI
In addition to the reduction in economic activity and rising unemployment, 2011 saw the sharpest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last decade. According to the Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the FDI from January to June was $630,597, a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to $5,143,312 in the same period last year.
For its part, the Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Agency for Economic Development) recorded a total investment of 17,280,000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In view of the economic crisis, the state government applied to the National Congress in July for a loan of 3,000,000,000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy. The national congress approved an amount of 200,600,000 pesos, but until November no positive effects of the debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be observed.
Reactions
For the representatives of the business community, Mario López Valdé's first year in office made it obvious that he was unable to govern.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico) stated that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonize the views of the different sectors, including the national government.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa has been really poor this year. We have to work hard to regain the ground lost this year and in 2012 we have to make a double effort. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well-coordinated government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year hampered and slowed down the country's economic development.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost. One of the most important impacts is a slowing economy, which is not sufficiently in motion to generate economic dynamism that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will close the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefining vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana in Sinaloa, said the need to encourage the state to engage in more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we observed that work was being done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There is a lot to do
The chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that better steers the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas where you can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
