Court approves transition to digital television in Mexico in 2015
The conversion from analog to digital signals has been one of the most important changes worldwide in recent years.
The Mexican Supreme Court (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional complaints filed by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree, which requires the switch from analogue to digital signals to be brought forward from 2021 to 2015, due to the lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his powers when he issued the decree-law detailing the switchover to digital terrestrial television.
With this decision, the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate was rejected because it did not obtain the necessary qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to decide on constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
In the project for the lawsuit, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed to declare the decree-law unconstitutional, since the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico) is responsible for regulating radio and television, so the legislative decree would contradict hierarchical principles and legal reservations.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero himself voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies lodged constitutional complaints against the legislative decree. Following the adoption of the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero ceased to apply the decree-law and ceased all activities relating to the establishment of digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint filed by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the debate on the project, for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his speech, the Prime Minister expressed that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the state government may not regulate with general regulations the measures that the public administration should take.
"I also don't think that if you did that, the independence of the regulator would be compromised." She also recalled that, for constitutional reasons, the planning of strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, is the responsibility of the central government, which directs state affairs.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that has taken place around the world in recent years, and it brings about better use of the radioelectric spectrum, increased quality of the signal and more channels.
Postponing the changeover, she said, is a postponement of the benefits of digitalisation, which is a decision in the public interest that does not only have technical aspects, "because it includes economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "required the action of the entire system, in accordance with the principle of economic management by the state, they included a set of features that the constitution places in the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries around the world had already carried out the digital switchover, through the government, even though they had highly specialised facilities.
It cannot be concluded that the government is encroaching on the powers of Congress by issuing the contested decree-law, because the laws passed by the legislature are being respected," she asserted.
The possibility of counting the ballots individually in Michoacán is being considered
According to PREP, the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is just under 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6,074 still to be counted.
The possibility of individual counting of ballots is a reality this year in the elections in Michoacán, because according to the data issued by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between the first and second place in the gubernatorial elections is just under 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 still not counted.
In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last 9th November the electoral office had adopted a series of regulations harmonizing local regulations with the reforms of the states in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, his electoral law or his law on electoral justice to the reforms passed by Congress, so that they did not enter into force in this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided publication in the State Gazette within the deadlines laid down for this purpose, arguing that he still had objections to it.
On November 9, Mexico's Supreme Court (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional complaint filed by the local legislature, ruling that the state commissioner's vote on the constitutional reforms was "invalid and unlawful" because he did not have the right to "decide or veto it."
María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained in an interview about the possibility of counting the votes individually that thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, it is now possible for the local electoral authority to count all or part of the ballots.
Thus, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted under the following conditions: The results in the minutes do not match; the minutes of the counting and calculation of votes are not available on file or are not in the possession of the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the overall counting of the completed ballot papers may take place if there is a difference between the presumed winner and the one in second place that is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an express request by the party or party representative. Coalition leader, who is the second of the above-mentioned candidates.
The counting of votes may also be carried out in its entirety if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is determined that the difference between the presumed winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose candidate came second. In this case, the electoral packages that have been subjected to partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation, where, according to PREP, the difference between first and second place is just under 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
