Formation of the new Italian government on Wednesday
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet the President of Italy tomorrow to present to him the new government to face the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet the President of Italy tomorrow to present to him the new government to face the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet on Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm the formation of the government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mainly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of talks with the political parties to form a government.
"I would like to reiterate my absolute confidence in our country's ability to cope with these difficult times," the former EU commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of the government, but his comments indicate that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "framework is now well defined," he added.
Monti managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than normal. Meanwhile, Italy is struggling with a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of debt to unbearable levels.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, must adopt a tough austerity package demanded by euro politicians in order to regain battered confidence in Italy.
The pressure to hurry on Monti was exacerbated by the fluctuating market situation, as a result of which Italian government bonds were burdened with 7 percent interest for 10 years. This corresponds to the situation at which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European rescue package.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of Confindustria, told the press after a meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government to the best of our ability."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to emerge from this emergency.
Monti's chances of success were greatly increased by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, who was forced to resign on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to produce good results," said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is essential, because so far many of its members have spoken out against a majority technocrat government that Monti is currently forming.
Support from Parliament
Monti's new government needs strong parliamentary support to implement the likely unpopular austerity measures.
Resistance to his efforts or the delay of reforms could once again provoke a devastating attack by financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks is also exerting pressure by pointing out that Monti's failure would be a disaster.
Monti began his debates on Monday with political parties, trade unions and employers' associations, as well as with youth and women's organisations.
The meeting is to be concluded on Tuesday evening.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who has launched an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
After a brief sigh of relief towards the end of last week, when it was announced that Berlusconi would resign, uncertainty over the success of the new prime minister has brought the cost of Italian government bonds back to critical levels.
A rescue of Italy with a national debt of 1.8 trillion euros would be too much for the current EU rescue package.
Monti said his government must last until the next elections, expected to be held in 2013, despite predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms instead of bringing the elections forward.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should consist only of technicians, an indication of their concerns about the procedure imposed by pressure from the financial markets.
Political sources point out that the mutual distrust and disagreements between the parties complicate the inclusion of people from political life.
