We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why?
I think that's partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs. Everyone likes a different song, so the decision which one we will play is not easy.
If we add two or three songs that we haven't played in a while, we can keep our concentration better and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs. Otherwise, they could be forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and I think that's why it's for the audience.
With this tour you celebrate your twenty years of history.
Looking back, is it hard for you to believe in your success?
Yes, totally.
First of all, I don't think any of us imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years. It seems like a dream.
We continue to rely on this blessing and think it's great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are passionate about making music.
We are lucky to be able to go to the places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean to you to have actively participated in the birth of grunge?
It has always been an honour to belong to this group of great bands.
We are good friends with the folks at Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and quite unusual for a movement to emerge from a group of friends.
Every now and then a band emerges from one city, but it's unusual for five or ten groups to come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We're excited to still be friends with them all, and we're honored to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It's also very unusual for a band like yours to stay with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago. That alone is much more time than many bands survive.
First of all, I believe that we are all lucky to be alive and we also take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give each individual the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and his music. We couldn't be better.
Your relationship with fame has not always been easy. On the other hand, thanks to your success, you were always able to do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we've grown has made it easier for us to find balance.
We make sure not to tour too often, because it's too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you think that people came for the music, it reminds you that you have to respect the music and what it has created without being obsessed with being a famous rock star. That never interested us anyway.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and at the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We're still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who built the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh together and talk about music and football and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and therefore chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos of several groups and we liked this band the most. That's why we're curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. That will certainly be exciting.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
From so many+
Among the first that comes to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could spend the whole afternoon talking about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge alive even though it's no longer a fad?
I think we all don't feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, the bands I mentioned earlier come to mind, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone else that came up at the same time. If they're still important today, I think that's great, because it's worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever before.
At first her music was darker, now it's more positive.
Why?
That's interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a bit frivolous. But there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive about them.
Tears came to both of them when I heard Ed play them. They are very dark songs.
I believe that when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life - for example, when you lose a family member or a friend - it affects your artistic work and your music and these two songs clearly embody that for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
Peru:
Fujimori came back to the hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to examine muscle loss in his legs, his family doctor informed.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving 25 years in prison for human rights violations during his reign (1990-2000), has several illnesses, including tongue cancer, who has been operated on four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a member of Congress and his personal doctor, told television that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas, Peruvian hospital, to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned on humanitarian grounds. Nevertheless, he did not want this because he considered him innocent.
He has had four operations on tongue cancer and has lost 18 kilos of weight. In addition, there are other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulation problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been in the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la policía since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the Peruvian army death squad, which was secretly active during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón next Wednesday. According to the Uruguayan president, this will be the culmination of his fully booked schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting between the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries," the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderón's support over the incident with France, when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that still act as tax havens. This statement was rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request to its ambassador to the European country.
Since November, Mexico has chaired the G20, a group made up of the world's most powerful emerging and industrialized countries. Since January of this year, there has been an agreement on the exchange of tax information with the South American country in order to avoid double assessment.
In recent years, the government of Uruguay has tried to speed up the concretization of agreements on the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD). On it are countries that have not introduced all international standards for cooperation in tax matters.
At the business level, a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has been in place since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
The mustachioed installer enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for 25 years to rescue Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never in three dimensions: in Super Mario 3D Land, he fights for the girl's love in stereo technology.
The game, which hits stores around the world this month, has been tailored from the outset to the characteristics of the Nintende 3DS portable console, which allows three-dimensional play without special glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to say how stereoscopy works without glasses," said Omar Álvarez, head of the Nintendo press in Spain, at the launch of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez explained that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first video game from Nintendo that has been developed for this console from the beginning", because until now successful articles such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
The spokesperson for Nintendo emphasized that although it is three-dimensional, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "affordable" video game that allows for fast-paced, smooth play.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" includes two games in one: the first part is "lightweight" to capture the less shymed users.
After that, the experts can "turn a second round" over the different game levels, which are becoming increasingly difficult.
Also, users can choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action. In order to overcome the obstacles, however, without becoming a victim of the "optical effects", it is always necessary to play three-dimensionally.
Super Mario's foray into the three-dimensional world also means the character's return to a portable console, which hasn't been the case since 2005.
With this video game, Nintendo winks at the fans of the saga and repeats the recipe for success of the last editions: The mustachioed plumber must overcome platforms riddled with dangers to free Princess Peach.
However, the player encounters news in the movements, the environment, the disguises and the enemies - and a "playable" Luigi.
Colom guarantees Portillo's extradition to the United States
Guatemalan President Álvaro Colom announced Tuesday that he would grant the extradition of former Governor Alfonso Portillo to answer for the $70 million conspiracy to launder in the United States.
Thus ends the trial of the US request for Portillo's extradition so that he can be tried there.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was based on the independence of the judiciary and the government, taking into account that a court had already ordered the extradition.
He stressed that during his government he had not interfered in court decisions and had granted all extradition requests of which he was informed.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín is extradited for murder and aggravated assault, Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Colom's actions are a government act that takes place when all judicial and constitutional bodies for sentencing the former president of the state (2000-2004) have been exhausted.
According to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court of Guatemala, Portillo must be extradited once his legal situation in Guatemala has been clarified and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted for embezzling 120 million quetzales in the Ministry of Defense during his reign. This trial preceded the extradition, but the minister lodged an objection and revived the case.
Trinijove has helped 6000 young people at risk of social exclusion
The organisation was created to avoid the marginalisation of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of life of the social welfare organisation Trinijove have led to important results: in this quarter of a century, 6000 young people threatened by social exclusion have been supported to find a way out of their difficult situation.
Added to this are the more than a hundred jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, an event was held yesterday in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, attended by more than 300 people.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the Trinitat Vella district with the aim of helping young people with a low level of education, without work, with drug problems threatened by the risk of marginality.
Yesterday's celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by numerous leaders of institutions and institutions that have worked with the association over these 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different tendencies during the election campaign demonstrated the impartiality of Trinijove's work.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the celebrations were attended by former Socialist Education Minister Ernest Maragall and former mayor and current left-green councillor Ricard Goma.
The great hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the General Director of the Social Work of the Savings Bank La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas emphasized that Trinijove was created in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated. But he added that the work done so far "is a good foundation."
For the President of the Generalitat, Trinijove is a role model who knows how to fight difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in difficulty.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the club and the work it does," he said.
Occupied house where huge parties were held was evicted
The homeowners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building at 51 Balmes Street (Barcelona).
The twelve squatters left the building yesterday afternoon without having put up any resistance.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of house No. 51 on Balmes Street have come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building they had illegally occupied and organized huge parties that had driven the neighborhood to despair yesterday at noon. The eviction was carried out by court order without police intervention.
After the eviction, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, access will be controlled," confirmed the property manager.
The squatters, who had occupied 11 of the building's 13 apartments - the rest were inhabited - took the entire electrical system and part of the water supply with them. In addition, they had painted the walls and left behind all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
Huge parties were held on the three lower floors, lasting up to two days, driving tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business had declined by 80% since the squatting began.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the squatters gave her unfair competition, because they sold the drinks for three euros, while they cost 10 euros in the discotheque.
In addition, the owner of the leisure venue had been reported by the neighbours for disturbing the peace, while, according to her, the noise did not come from the visitors of the disco, but from the squatters and, in particular, from the guests of the parties that were organised there, which, according to the angry neighbours, have become more and more and longer in recent weeks.
The person in charge of the discotheque explained that the harassment was so great that she agreed with the owner of the building not to have to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (municipal police) also confirmed that they had received more complaints from neighbours in recent weeks.
The leader of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in the Barcelona City Council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, had demanded last week that the building be evacuated immediately and that the problems of civic coexistence and the deterioration of the district be brought under control.
He explained that before the summer, only one floor of the building was occupied, but that in recent months the squatters had penetrated all floors of the building and almost all apartments. In some there had even been thefts.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and crack down on the anti-social acts in the building."
Yesterday, another building in the Nou Barris district was evacuated by the Catalan police.
At 3:30 p.m., police approached 35 Montral Street after receiving a call from a neighbor who witnessed four people trying to enter the building.
The four were immediately arrested.
Park or mountain?
Apart from the disputes over the fees, the architects agree with the tender.
The municipal tender for the 16 gates reopens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now disappeared Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration published its diatribe about the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
It has even been compared in numbers to New York's Central Park.
With the demise of the CMB in 1987, the park once again became the upper limit of Barcelona in the eyes of many, because the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that does not spread north-south, but up (mountains) and down (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a nature park plays with this idea.
The model was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars in the role of the yogi bear.
This was the case when the city issued a huge tender in September, consisting of 16 competitions, for further access gates to Collserola.
Undoubtedly, a gate refers to the concept of a park.
Either this is the case, or someone intends to put gates in the countryside.
The question arises naturally: Collserola, park or mountain?
The tender is the topic of conversation not only from an organizational point of view, but also in terms of reflection on the city, in the mouths of all architects from Barcelona.
It is almost a recurring theme that two members of this long-established caste who meet in the elevator can fall back on.
And it is precisely this fact that provides the material for one of the rare similarities between what three architects from Barcelona think about it and some university professors who have applied for the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The call is appropriate.
For Roldán, "it is necessary" to talk about the "front on the mountains" after the attack on the coast, as far as the discourse of Ildefons Cerda, the one on the green apples, has not been carried out.
"One should start from the principle that Barcelona's largest park is the beach.
Among other things, because it is easily accessible.
Collserola is more complex," says the architect, for whom the title "Gates of Collserola" contains a "lexical trap": one must not "imagine it as access to a park, but as a delimitation of areas where action must be taken."
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with urban planning experience, sees the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" that carries "some dangers".
Dangers resulting from the "uncertainty that the design of a public space brings with it today" after the experiences of the 1980s, which had their "swan song" in the area of the Forum.
The first fear is one's own limitation to what may be built.
"To narrow something down always means to determine the next step", i.e. to exceed it.
"You have to think about new urban planning tools, because the current ones [referring to the Plan General Metropolitano (PGM)] can lead to a real disaster."
Modol, who sticks more closely to the question, says simply that the side of Collserola that goes towards Vallesana "can be understood as a park, the one towards Barcelona cannot", for purely topographical reasons.
Modol recalls that there is already a study by the Patronat de Collserola, which should not "fall on deaf ears", although he is grateful to the city administration for giving its committee the opportunity to participate in this project "from the first moment".
In addition, he notes that the proximity of the mountains to the city is the letter of safe conduct that allows architects to participate in the debate, although he expresses his "doubts" as to whether this technical profile should guide the multidisciplinary teams created ("just the right thing," he says).
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the title of this article is complex, as the tender conditions lack a global view of Collserola: "There were 16 competitions in cross-section," he says, "on the mountain-sea axis. But there is no longitudinal perspective that looks at the area as a whole."
At least in his case, this has led to him taking part in the 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the program and definition of a project for a gate would collide with that of the architect of the gate next to it.
In his opinion, the city should guarantee that the strip directly above the Ronda de Dalt is equipped along its entire length in such a way as to create a soft transition between the city and green zones.
Casino awards Jonás Larrazábal who comes free
After 72 days of silence, the representative of Casino Red freed the brother of the mayor of Monterrey from the trial against him for alleged extortion.
After 72 days in captivity, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal is released after Casino Red's representative forgives him in the district's Second Criminal Court, which is conducting the trial of the brother of the mayor of Monterrey for extortion.
After the attack on the Casino Royale, Sergio Gil García, the owner of Casino Red, published a series of photos and videos showing Manuel Jonás, allegedly forcing him to pay a sum of money so that the city administration approved the secret operation of the betting house.
Following the criminal complaint, the public prosecutor's office opened criminal proceedings against the brother of the panicked mayor, who was arrested for 30 days on September 2.
After four hours with the official of the Ministerio Público 3 en Delitos Patrimoniales, he was taken to Casa de Arraigo 1 in the Barrio Antiguo of the capital.
He remained in this place for 49 days after a second arrest warrant, after the official of the Ministerio Público had rejected the crimes of bribery and organized crime.
On October 19, he was transferred to the Cadereyta detention center for allegedly bribing the owners of Casino Red with one and a half million pesos. On the other hand, he only stayed in the middle security wing for a few hours due to death threats against him.
The authorities allowed him to participate in the trial as an inmate of the municipal prison of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On October 25, he was served with a detention order by the secretary of the district's Second Criminal Court, Jorge Yánez. He stated that after almost two months of investigations, there was sufficient evidence to find Jonás guilty of paying 1.5 million pesos to the representatives of the betting house in exchange for opening it.
This Monday, the representative of Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, asked Judge José Luis Pecina to release the mayor's brother from the sentence and he will be released in the next few hours.
During the court hearing, Ramiro Arias, the official of the Ministerio Público assigned to the court, asked García Gómez whether he had repaired the damage and which of the owner of the betting house had expressed his forgiveness. However, the lawyer withheld the name.
In accordance with Case 197/2011, Jonás Larrazábal is acquitted. In the following, too, no objections can be filed against the process, and no damages are claimed.
After hearing the representative of the betting house at around 3:50 p.m., Larrazabal Bretón was immediately released.
The court secretary, Jorge Yánez, went to the municipal prison of San Nicolás de los Garza to inform Jonás that he had been acquitted and that his case would be closed.
He also informed him of the court order for immediate release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash that killed government secretary Francisco Blake and seven other people.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat for Communications and Transport in Mexico) informed that the investigation into the accident that killed government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people indicate that the helicopter with its entire intact structure hit the ground without the pilot being able to initiate an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, secretary for communications and transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before take-off that the weather conditions had been suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller blades were in contact with trees at a height of 25 meters, with the helicopter losing its fuselage, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for transporting the personnel.
In addition, he said that during the investigations in the area where the plane had come down, no helicopter parts were found.
"During the search, no aircraft parts were found elsewhere, the impact affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has a slope of 7 to 30 degrees.
At present, the priority is to receive the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but this could take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, General Director of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Emergency Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter from the Estado Mayor Presidencial had flown at cruising speed on impact and the aircraft had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of impact."
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of visual flight. This means that the crew should have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at launch. During the onward flight towards the border area between Mexico City and the Mexico State, some low-hanging clouds gathered.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that because of the clouds, the crew had chosen a lower area with better visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Point of impact:
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter match. There may have been no loss of control over the aircraft or deviation from the flight path prior to the impact.
Scattering the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available to date indicates that the helicopter had hit from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered remains of the aircraft suggests that the helicopter with its intact structure had hit the ground.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft at the scene of the accident do not indicate either fire or explosion.
The latest test results indicate several ground contacts.
During the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is sloping and has a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a meticulous search in an area that went beyond the cordoned-off area at the scene of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, reinforcing the assumption that the intact aircraft structure had crashed into the ground.
MSS announces research protocol to find the gene for obesity
She is leading a research project to find the gene for childhood and adolescent obesity, supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Institute of Mexico) announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents entitled "Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence", with the aim of finding the genetic markers associated with overweight.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers has been established.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The general public is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the sports fields of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are carried out every Saturday from 8.00 am.
He emphasized that the investigation began at the sports field of Cuauhtémoc (in the west of the state of Mexico) and has been continuing since October 8 at the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of Mexico).
If the target of 500 to 600 subjects is reached, the study will continue on the sports field of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and completed on that of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the goal of the study is to learn about the factors and role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents in the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of World Diabetes Day, he said the aim was for three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 to complete nutrition-related questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They are also asked questions about their physical activity and family history to control risk factors that may result in diabetes or kidney failure.
He also explained that on these Saturdays the subjects were measured (weight, height, waist circumference), their blood pressure was checked and blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (attempt to identify genes related to childhood obesity) were determined.
Cruz López stressed that this research was carried out in response to health workers' concerns about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"Health surveys conducted in 1999 and 2006 found that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent. Obesity has also risen dramatically," emphasized the IMSS specialist.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico was different from that of other peoples.
He stated that a Mexican is, on average, 65 percent Indian-American, 30 percent European, and 5 percent African, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
More generally, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess of energy (calories) we consume, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the study participants would be a comprehensive examination of the children to determine whether they had a degree of overweight or obesity.
It would even investigate the occurrence of dark skin folds in the neck and on the inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and diabetes in the preliminary stage.
All information would be treated confidentially and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors. Doctors explain all the measurement results to parents and suggest lifestyle changes that are appropriate to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors responsible for overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, i.e. lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, that is, an increased consumption of sugared drinks and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake, as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt from the UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM, develops asphalts modified with polymers to make the compound more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If attention were paid to the signs emanating from the road surface, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200,000 potholes when the rainy season breaks out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (urban area of the Valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warning and assuring that if the laying and maintenance of the asphalt surface were done appropriately,  the number of potholes can be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Potholes from a technical point of view", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the occurrence of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphaltenes - and the other part a low one - the so-called malthenes. Together, they give the road surface its characteristic viscoelastic behaviour.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, very viscous at 120°C and almost solid at 50°C, while it becomes brittle at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," explained the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City mostly have a flexible road surface composed of six layers of material, the last three of which contained asphalt.
Between the uppermost layers lies a layer of asphalt wear consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be distributed even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Above the wear layer," he explained, "a final layer is laid out, the so-called base layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand that has also been bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, they require greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it must create friction.
Since this road surface receives and distributes the most forces, the base course also needs an adequate thickness and the material it is made of must be maintained.
Weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes damp, water enters the layer and is difficult to escape. This causes a softening of all layers of the road surface and, as a result, the appearance of potholes.
When a pothole occurs," he said, "the surface layer is removed first, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. But the damage is not immediate, it is a process that should be maintained at the first sign by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of potholes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of road surface must always be proportionate to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which potholes could be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
