Such was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last November 4, a laphoscopist from the Investigation Unit of the Public Prosecutor's Office (CTI) from Cali arrived as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia): "Alfonso Cano" by comparing fingerprints.
Of the seven laphoscopists in the CTI department, Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years, was on call this week.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities of Chocó, where he often had to go into the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies he was supposed to identify were.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the necessary courses, he specialized in lopphoscopy, which is the examination of the skin exposed to friction, i.e. the palms and feet.
In the week of the operation against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big awaited him.
Friday night he flew by helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he was to identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one might be that of the man who had led the oldest guerrilla in the world. Therefore, he should take the ten-finger impression sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name) with him.
However, when he reached the place where the body was located, he could not identify him because of his physical appearance, which did not resemble the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a local farmer, wore no glasses, and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a trowel and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those on the imprint sheet.
He had seen correctly: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of informing the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was indeed the head of the FARC.
In search of clues
For a dactyloscope from the Sijín in Cali, the tribute paid by President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the mission against "Cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in resolving a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify corpses, they also support investigations into murders and robberies and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When arrested, many offenders present false identity documents or they do not have any.
We take their fingerprints and search for them in the database.
The researcher told us that he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house during a theft, because the thief had propped himself up with his hand at this very spot when he pulled out a safe stuffed with jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting. But in this case, we were able to take the imprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
With the help of fingerprints, murder suspects can also be exonerated or incriminated.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
During the investigation, it was suspected that a family member might be a suspect, and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, it is associated with the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that "the fingerprints would be taken from the object using chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a plant trowel or ribbon is used to take away.
After that, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil registry office.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identity papers," explained the expert from CTI.
He said that not everything was as it was portrayed in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything you glitter is gold, not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make an appropriate comparison.
