Compared to their European neighbours, French workers are therefore no more prone to incapacity for work than elsewhere.
A long-term study conducted in 2010 by two researchers from the French National Centre for the Study of Science (CNRS) showed that between 1994 and 2001 the global absenteeism rate (due to illness or otherwise) oscillated, ranging from 10% to 11% in France against 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Fraud in sick leave represents a negligible proportion of undeclared work.
As far as fraud is concerned, only a weak level is achieved here.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 means that there are systematic controls on sick leave exceeding 45 days.
