Euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized, according to a panel of experts
Canadians live in denial of death, according to a report by the Royal Society of Canada
The panel explained that governments, health care institutions and doctors are working together on pain-relieving treatment to provide the best pain-relieving remedies, beyond cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in an attitude of denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians actually agree to talk to their doctor about conditions under which they want to die and make arrangements for this purpose.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which involved six experts linked in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
This body recommends that the government amend the penal code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia where this choice arises, for patients who are considered capable of making such a decision.
As a prelude, the experts cite a recently published survey by the independent society EIU, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "medical euthanasia in Canada has created a culture where people are afraid to raise the issue of death."
Medical care or not: 77% of Canadians do not have access to painkillers, according to experts appointed by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the majority desire of Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them ultimately die in hospital.
Across the country, the rate of 86% hospital deaths is highest in Quebec.
On the thorny issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that run counter to the position of the federal government, which has already stated that it does not want to make any changes to the penal code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Now, however, according to the experts who have equally inspected all those countries whose approach has legalized or decriminalized euthanasia and assisted suicide, there is no evidence that such decriminalization would lead to misuse in their application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide of incompetent or non-consenting persons.
On the contrary, there are many more cases of such violations in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized, as Jocelyn Downie, co-signatory of the report, confirmed yesterday in a teleconference.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assisted suicide is also practiced in Canada, although clearly illegal here," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians advocate euthanasia
Remember that according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010, 85% of Canadians had already spoken out in favor of euthanasia, believing that it allows people at the end of their lives to alleviate their suffering.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia does not convey the message that the lives of elderly or disabled people have less value.
With regard to people who have already committed assisted suicide, 41% of respondents believe that they should not be prosecuted.
As far as maintaining or discontinuing drugs in patients is concerned, the situation is less clear, according to the authors of the report.
They also suggest in their list of recommendations that the criminal law should state that the withdrawal of funds for which there has been a valid refusal should not be regarded as criminal.
The panel of experts also calls for health professionals to be trained to respect end-of-life withdrawals without fear of prosecution.
The panel explained that governments, health care institutions and doctors are working together on pain-relieving treatment to provide the best pain-relieving agents, beyond cancer cases.
Finally, with regard to the means of pain relief or life-ending measures already widely used in Canadian health care institutions, the Panel calls for at least consideration to be given to them, as they do not serve to reduce physical pain any more than euthanasia and relate to the same procedures.
Reservations of other experts
Some experts in the field of public health have already expressed reservations about the conclusions of the Royal Society of Canada's expert report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, described the attitude of the report-signing experts as "extreme", as it sets no limits to the practice of euthanasia among sick people in the final phase.
"This opens the doors to a situation where anyone who is tired of life and older than 18 years asks another person to help him commit suicide," said Deschamps, who reviewed a summary of the report yesterday.
Attorney Deschamps also emphasizes that the authors of the report seemed to place individual ownership above all other values involved in the social fabric of society.
Now, he says, there are "guidelines and obligations in a society."
Margaret Somerville, a specialist in health law, has also expressed "strong opposition" to the report's conclusions, which she dubbed a 'pro-euthanasia manifesto'.
In particular, Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, questions the reporting data regarding the absence of abuses in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, such as the Netherlands and Oregon.
The King of Jordan calls on President Assad to step down from power
Damascus denounces 'plot'
Syria is increasingly isolated
Bashar al-Assad's partisans demonstrated yesterday in front of the Foreign Ministry authorities.
Diplomatic pressure on Bashar al-Assad's Syria, which, thanks to Russia's support, is resisting it and rejecting a "plot" against the country, intensified yesterday.
Two days before the exclusion of Syria by the Arab League, the European Union has tightened its sanctions against Damascus, despite the fact that Turkey and Jordan, Syria's neighbours, had taken a position in favour of President Assad's departure.
King Abdullah II Jordan yesterday was the sitting Arab prime minister who called on President Bashar al-Assad to "resign his power in Syria," in which some forty civilians and members of government power have already been killed.
"If Bashar cared about his country's interests, he would step down, but he should also create the necessary conditions for a new era of Syrian political life," the King of Jordan, Syria's neighbor, said in an interview with the BBC.
For his part, Turkish diplomatic chief Ahmet Davutoglu complained that the Turkish mediation attempts directed at the Syrian regime since the beginning of the year had not been crowned with success.
"Those in the Middle East who are not at peace with their people and cannot satisfy them must go," he said, alluding to Syria, the neighboring country to which Turkey is taking an increasingly harsh stance.
For its part, the United States welcomed the "intensification of the consensus against Assad and the machinations of the Syrian regime" following the decisions of the Arab League and the European Union.
"The international community, the United States, the EU, the Arab League and countries like Turkey have adopted an increasingly harsh tone in the face of repression in Syria," said Mark Toner, a spokesman for the state department.
During this time, 16 civilians and at least 19 members of government power have died in the Dar'a region of southern Syria, according to the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (OSDH).
Two other civilians were killed in "gunfire exchanges and heavy bombings around Jobar" in the besieged city of Homs, according to the NGO.
At a press conference, Syrian Foreign Trade Minister Walid al-Muallim said the country was "heading for the end of the crisis."
He has also reacted forcefully to the Arab League's decision to suspend Damascus from its duties, which he considers to be a "dangerous step".
Syria "will not give in," he added, asserting that "the plots forged against Syria will fail."
Following the decision to suspend Syria, the Arab League is now investigating a "protection mechanism for civilians" and wants 500 members of Arab human rights organizations, the media and military observers to be sent to the country.
The French Minister of Foreign Trade, Alain Juppé, had also spoken out in favour of sending UN observers to protect civilians from repression by the regime, which encapsulates itself in its "paranoia".
An unscheduled new meeting of the League is scheduled for tomorrow in Rabat to discuss the implementation of the crisis exit plan adopted on November 2, but in particular the controversial and expected withdrawal of military troops from the besieged cities and the liberation of imprisoned demonstrators.
Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov yesterday described the Arab League's decision as "incorrect" in order to be wary of advocating possible sanctions against Damascus, even though China had already urged Syria to implement the crisis exit plan.
Italy
Monti calls on markets to be patient and Italy to sacrifice
Mario Monti, Italy's future head of government, has asked the markets for a little more time to form his staff and implement a programme that demands "sacrifices" in order to regain the creditworthiness lost during the last months of the Berlusconi government.
The former EU Commissioner held a hearing with the political parties yesterday ahead of today's meeting between trade unions and employers.
It was his job to convene a cabinet in parliament composed relatively strictly of external technocrats.
"Monti spoke of an important programme with a number of victims," said Francesco Nucara, a member of one of the many smaller parliamentary groups participating in the talks, after meeting the President-in-Office of the Council.
For his part, Gianfranco Fini, President of the Chamber of Deputies, had promised Mario Monti to give Parliament a vote of confidence by Friday to ensure that the new government had sufficient support.
The agreements will culminate in the presentation by M. Monti of a list of deletions, which will undoubtedly range from a dozen ministers to the head of state, Giorgio Napolitano.
M. Monti commented that yesterday's nervousness of the stock exchange and bond markets demanded its time.
In "a democracy, there are certain deadlines" to prepare a government and a government programme, he stressed, noting that it was "certain that the markets will be tolerant and reasonable".
His appointment by the president was initially welcomed by the markets, but the unrest had intensified again, especially after an unexpected decline in industrial production in the eurozone in September.
The incumbent prime minister should set up a staff consisting mainly of technocrats, although he had stressed that he would also like to include "politicians".
The new government should only last until 2013, the date of the next parliamentary elections, he estimated.
According to Gianfranco Fini, the president of the Chamber of Deputies, the new government should receive the vote of confidence of the parliament by Friday.
Since taking up his post, M. Monti has committed himself to working as a matter of urgency towards the goal of making Italy a "new protagonist" in Europe.
A spokesman for EU Commissioner Olli Rehn had stressed that "our diagnosis of the Italian economy does not change, even taking into account the new government".
In particular, the EU, convinced that Rome will not achieve its goal of balancing the budget in 2013 despite the austerity plans taken up in recent months, has requested new hardship measures.
Emma Marcegaglia, "head of the bosses" of Italy, who will meet Monti on Tuesday, also insists on the need to stimulate the economy, "because a country that has no growth at all cannot respect the deficit indicators".
M. Monti, who is known for his competence and his independence as EU Commissioner (1994-2004), stands for an "epochal change" of Italy after 17 years of "Berlusconism"; the "professor" symbolizes the "challenge of trustworthiness" as well as a "different Italy," according to the editorialists.
The big unknown here is the longevity of his staff.
President Napolitano would like to prevent early elections, as Italy has to pay for 200 billion euros in government bonds from now until April 2012.
Russian scientist helps Iran's nuclear energy program
A Russian scientist, Vyacheslav Danilenko, has helped Iran develop a detonator that can be used with a nuclear weapon, an American NGO specializing in nuclear risks confirmed on Monday.
The Institute for Science and International Security ISIS bases the result on the recently published report of the International Agency for Atomic Safety AIEA as well as other documents emanating from this UN agency to identify this scientist.
The AIEA last week expressed its "serious concern" about a "possible military dimension" of Iran's nuclear program.
According to detailed study of the AIEA documents by ISIS, Danilenko, born in 1934, had apparently worked for over three decades in a Soviet military nuclear center in Chelyabinsk (Urals) since the beginning of the 60s and was involved in the explosion-generated production of synthetic diamonds.
In 1989 or 1991 he is said to have left the center to found a company in Kiev that produces "nano-diamonds".
The economic difficulties of his company led him to contact the Iranian embassy in Ukraine in 1995.
Before returning to Russia, he then worked on an Iranian programme from 1996 to 2002.
In its latest report, the AIEA mentioned "strong indications that Iran's development of a nuclear explosives system" had been aided by the work of a foreign expert who was not only highly skilled in this technique, but also, as a state official told the agency, had spent his entire professional career working on this technology directly on the military nuclear energy program of his country of origin."
Anti-Islamic crimes and offenses have increased by 50%
Crimes and offenses against Muslims increased by 50% from 2009 to 2010, while other racially or religiously motivated violent crimes either decreased slightly or increased only slightly over the same period, according to FBI statistics released Monday.
According to these data, the total number of violent crimes committed against Muslims increased from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, i.e. by 49%, while there was a 13% increase in violent crimes against Catholics, a 4% decrease in crimes against Jews and a global increase of 14% in anti-religious crimes and crimes.
The total number of "hate crimes" rose to 6,628 cases at a very low rate, including 47.3% motivated by racial differences and 20% by religious differences, according to the FBI.
"After a slowdown in 2009, it is disturbing to see these crimes and offenses grow again," Human Rights First said. The increase in anti-Islamic violence is particularly significant," the organization added in a communiqué.
"Human Rights First has long emphasized that violence against Muslims, as well as all forms of hate crimes, should be considered a serious violation of human rights," added Paul Legendre, an organization's official.
"The American government can and should do more to combat these attacks," he added, noting that this could be done by improving police attitudes toward "hate crimes."
The "hate crime" in US federal law presents itself as a legacy from the era of the struggle for civil rights.
This legislation was passed after the death of Martin Luther King to punish acts of violence directed against race, color, religion or descent and now also includes crimes of sexual affiliation.
