Austria
Entry of a "Golden Budgetary Rule" in the Constitution
The government of the grand Social Democrat/Christian Democratic coalition in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to include a "Golden Budget Rule" in the constitution in order to reduce public deficits and also avoid possible degradation by rating agencies in Austria's top credit rating (AAA).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision of the outcome of the Council of Ministers, although the public public debt of Austria stands at 74.6%, i.e. far above the criterion of 60% laid down by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debt level of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency had not fallen from AAA to AA+ in one fell swoop, we would have to pay an additional three billion euros in interest every year," argued Michael Spindelegger, Vice-Chancellor and Christian Democratic Foreign Minister.
Austria also acceded to a demand made by the Brussels summit of euro area member states on 26th October that the heads of state and government had demanded the inclusion of the reduction of public deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to public balance in the constitution or by enacting an equivalent law.
The action taken by the Austrian government is similar to the 'German model', since Germany was the first European country to include such a 'rule' in its constitution.
By 2017, the structural budget deficit should decrease by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) every year, from 2017 the structural budget deficit of the state should not exceed the 0.35% of GDP limit, while the regional states as well as the municipalities should have balanced budgets.
The aim is to eradicate budget debt below the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Agreement over the horizon of 2020/21.
Strong Yen
Noda threatens a new intervention in the currency markets
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda warned on Tuesday that Japanese authorities would intervene again in currency markets if the yen continued to rise.
"If we see excessive volatility 'in the exchange rate of the yen,' we will intervene as we did last time," M. Noda said in the Senate.
On Tuesday, the yen had again rebounded close to the historical levels that forced Japanese authorities to intervene on October 31.
On that day, Tokyo had massively sold yen against dollars in order to lower the value of Japan's foreign exchange, which is heading for a new record since 1945 against the dollar.
However, the yen has risen steadily above this, doped by purchases by investors who see the yen as a "safe haven" in these uncertain times of global economic downturn and debt crisis in Europe.
The dollar fell below 77 yen on Tuesday, the euro slipped below the symbolic 105 yen bar near the levels that triggered the last intervention.
Before the 2008-2009 financial crisis, the dollar was trading around 120 yen and the euro more than 160 yen.
This flash in the pan of the Japanese currency harms the archipelago's exports, as it increases the cost of "Made in Japan" products and reduces the income value drawn by Japanese companies from abroad, as they exchange them into local currency.
"Japan is fighting for its reconstruction after the earthquake and tsunami on March 11, which devastated the Tohoku region (northeast)," emphasizes M. Noda, who fears that this increase in yen prices could already kill the weak upswing in the bud.
With growth in the third quarter -1.5% compared to the previous quarter, the third world economy has regained traction for the first time this year thanks to the sharp increase in exports and the consumption of households "sealed" by the disaster.
However, the prime minister estimates that yen inflation does not reflect "Japan's economic foundations."
For his part, Finance Minister Jun Azumi called on the Bank of Japan (BoJ), which opened a two-day meeting of its monetary policy committee on Tuesday, to take all possible measures to weaken the yen.
However, Hirohide Yamaguchi, deputy governor of the institute, has informed that the BoJ has already taken "appropriate measures", announcing that no additional currency easing is expected on Wednesday.
At the last meeting at the end of October, the central bank increased its government bond purchases by 5,000 billion yen (47 billion euros) to repay the 55,000 billion yen (519 billion euros) of coverage it had spent on various purchases of financial securities to flood the liquidity market.
Euro area:
Interest rates soar, stock markets pull back
The risk of contagion from the debt crisis is constantly undermining European indicators.
Despite the inauguration of the new heads of government in Greece and Italy and the best growth figures in France and Germany, the rates of the weakened countries continue to rise steadily.
Stock markets, which are still concerned about the stability of the eurozone, are drifting a little further into negative territory this Tuesday, November 15.
In Paris, the CAC lost 1.4% at 10 a.m., falling to 3,064 points.
The Dax in Frankfurt fell by 0.4%, London by 0.1%.
"Due to the new tensions over government bond yields in the troubled eurozone, global equity markets continue to issue some of their recent gains.
"Investors are nervous and only too aware of the risk of contagion," Terry Pratt, institutional broker at IG Markets, told Reuters.
The Tokyo stock exchange, which for its part is suffering from renewed fears among market participants about capacity in Europe that the debt crisis will continue, closed with a bear market of 0.7%.
"Japan, like the rest of the world, has its eyes on Europe, and trading is on a limited variational corridor as long as investors do not have evidence that the situation has stabilized," said Mitsushige Akino, fund manager at Ichiyoshi Investment Management.
This resurgence of concern about the eurozone's future is damaging the single currency, which continues its bear market on Tuesday.
The euro has been at its lowest level for a month and a half.
At 10 a.m., the European currency was worth 1.3570 dollars, falling by 0.4%.
According to the stockbrokers, it has declined after the CDU, the party of Chancellor Angela Merkel, who met in Congress on Monday, granted a request that, in particular, provides for the possibility for countries in difficulty to leave the eurozone without leaving the European Union at the same time.
The Italian and Spanish rates are well below the 6% mark.
Lending rates in Italy and Spain remain at very worrying levels.
This Tuesday morning, the yield on Italian bonds reached 6.85% over 10 years, while that on Spanish bonds matured to 6.2%.
