The incoming Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, called on the markets to give more time to restore the situation in Italy, which is threatened by paralysis due to the debt burden.
For his part, the new Greek Prime Minister, Lucas Papademos, confirmed that implementing the decisions taken at the euro zone summit on 27th October was "the main task" of his government.
Spain is in the sights of the markets as parliamentary elections take place in the country on Sunday.
The interest rate gap ("spread") between German and Spanish 10-year bonds has once again reached a new, historic high.
Awaiting Eurozone growth figures
Statistically, France recorded economic growth of 0.4% in the third quarter, supported by household consumption, slightly better than the expected 0.3%.
However, the Federal Statistical Office INSEE had revised the bear market in the figures for the second quarter, with a minus of 0.1% of gross domestic product (GDP) instead of stagnation.
In truth, it is the fourth quarter that worries economists the most.
Germany, for its part, recorded growth of 0.5% over the same period.
A first projection of the entire Eurozone is expected at 11 a.m., with the EU Commission warning of the risk of another recession.
Energy policy:
Facts should triumph over dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, it is certainly energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity have a direct influence on the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to take an election meeting as an opportunity to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by 2050 if an enormous proportion of the world's population does not have to do without a vital element.
At the same time, it is necessary to alleviate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to be able to continue to produce electricity consistently, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to combat climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident did not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany continues to be isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which subordinates its decision to the need to find a substitute source, nor in Switzerland, which only intends to build last-generation nuclear power stations.
The United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
For its part, after Fukushima, the United States decided to add another unit to its park by reopening the Three Mile Island plant, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Even if the German model, which focuses on renewable energy sources, is sometimes presented as a model, reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will be reflected in an increase in the price of electricity, increased energy dependence, especially on Russia, due to the increased use of imported gas, and an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal-fired power plants.
All these unpleasant effects will become noticeable within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives cause for reflection.
On the one hand, Denmark is the European leader in terms of wind energy, from which it obtains 30% of its electricity, and on the other hand, it is one of the largest users of coal and gas, alternated with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and electricity prices are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
Since the price of energy plays a key role in competitiveness in the globalised economy and a guarantee of stability for industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage because of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore lead to a sharp increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Polls have shown that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are no more willing to pay than they show resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125,000 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a plethora of specialised small and medium-sized enterprises to international markets and makes them creators of countless jobs.
If France were to decide to phase out nuclear power, a large proportion of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the €6 billion a year in capital goods and nuclear exports would shrink more and more.
What electrician would hire an EPR designed to work for sixty years when the decline of its producer is inevitable?
In order to solve the energy equation, one must admit that there is no miracle cure for the generation of electricity any more than a devil's work.
The low-CO2 solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy testify to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a safety authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent inspections in existing plants, such as the construction site in Flamanville.
Their work teams, which have made a name for themselves due to their professionalism, are just too obsessed with the idea of security.
In 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, at Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; so it proceeded without consequences for man and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was evoked by reactor construction and indefinable human error.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented proportions, which caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn the same lessons from this accident as it did after the previous two.
As a result of this approach, as well as a cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR represents a blueprint that allows it to be resilient to such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among electrical engineers to build a nuclear power station, a halt to construction in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition from Areva and EDF, giving them free rein to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is inevitable and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party maneuvers dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
Nicolas Sarkozy's immigration policy has been criticised from many angles - overloading police, judicial and administrative bodies due to a policy based on numbers, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France had called itself.
Recently, the harassment of foreign students by the authorities had dominated the newsreels, with the Minister of the Interior casually proclaiming (see Libération of 23 May) that France "did not need talents, bricklayers or waiters from abroad".
But this policy has rarely been analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus between the right and the left on this issue.
On the right, the tone was struck by Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", on the left by Michel Rocard, who had argued in 1990 that France "could not absorb all the poverty in the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity
The fear of the invasion of national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared by both the right and the left in 2005.
Both camps perceived immigrants as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that one is willing to admit towards immigrants.
François Hollande's programme confines himself to banalities that suggest that partnership development makes it possible to solve our "migration problems".
This idea of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on elections; However, it is economically costly.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron remind us in a recent work summarizing the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of the flood of immigrants on economic growth.  Wages and jobs in the countries of immigration.
Restricting immigration would weaken growth and damage the labour market situation.
Fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to replace domestic workers, especially the less skilled, by putting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than native wage workers, as they mainly work in sectors that are underutilised in terms of jobs.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not appeal to native wage workers, the more qualified immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not matched to labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would find it difficult to work in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, this complementarity between natives and migrants also has a positive effect of immigrant influx on wages and the domestic labour market.
In this way, Giovanni Peri has calculated that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants would lead to a long-term increase in real wages of between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants is conducive to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, PayPal, eBay, and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also make a net contribution to social systems, averaging about 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organization, for example, estimates that a person immigrating to Germany at the age of 30 makes an average net contribution (income minus expenses) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wished to bring about the missing points of intersection "with his teeth" when he took office.
However, these teeth, which were supposed to deter the immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, now it remains to think through European democracy
Democracy is a precious commodity; also a sensitive commodity.
The European continent should be able to remember for itself who, after its invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, endured the tragedies of the First World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and the colonel in Greece.
Some may have believed that it was enough to exercise the right to vote, in the most direct way possible, to see democracy prevail once and for all over its enemies.
It has been known since Napoleon "the Small" that it was a feature of attitude.
Universal suffrage, which is a necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition for this and can just as well become an "instrument of oppression", as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot put it at the time.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social community spirit, justice.
The crisis in Europe in which we find ourselves is an economic crisis, but it is just as much and first and foremost a political and democratic crisis.
The change of heart of the Greek true-false referendum would have been doubly revealing in this respect: on the one hand, that of the need for a vigorous return of politics, but on the other hand, that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, its inappropriateness.
This ambivalence should be considered outdated.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have shifted today, and that Republican soldiers, or at least most of them, are no longer aiming in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain in order to press for the success of the national referendum, which was organised according to necessity and in the wrong order.
A free pass for the European autocrat or a blindfolded leap into the emptiness of nationalist retreat: a great choice for the citizen!
No, we want Hackebeil, but a collective task, full of law, clarified and steady, an election and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain and Portugal - we do not know where to end the list - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that bows to the dictates of the markets and the rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated at international level.
There is concern about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is gradually losing its sovereignty, and thus every single one of the nations affiliated to it.
The urgency is to put the leadership of the European project back in hand with popular sovereignty.
After all, it is up to the whole whether Europeans can reduce the burden of their debt, free themselves from the markets and pave the way for a future through investment.
