"Contactless" smart cards are becoming common property
The world trade fair for chip cards opens its doors on Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris in an optimistic attitude.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 was supposed to end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor chips (debit cards, SIM card phones), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most important segment here is contactless technology, which allows payments on public transport or payment of purchases by simply holding the card up to a reader.
Compared to the 320 million sold a year earlier, 460 million contactless chip cards should be sold worldwide this year!
Their market share should continue to grow in 2012 (580 million units expected) and represent over 10% of the global chip card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe is gaining ground in contactless payment after lagging behind the Asia-Pacific region for a long time.
Some 26 million Visa cards are already equipped with this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless Visa cards were distributed.
However, the hypermarkets are gaining steam.
Carrefour has therefore issued 2.5 million contactless passport MasterCards this year.
In order to move to higher speeds, it is now necessary for banks to equip their customers with these cards.
"Two major French financial institutions have committed to systematically hand out contactless bank cards to their customers in the future," announced Gérard Nébouy, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by mobile phone
However, this is only a first step on the way to the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
A negligible percentage of devices have so far been equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology necessary to carry out these transactions.
"You have fallen behind".
"But they should at least experience a real upward trend next year."
"We expect to sell 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012," explains Marc Bertin, Chairman of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the initiative.
Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees are to be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
BPCE is running a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And Société Générale also said yesterday that it was preparing the launch of an offer that would allow its customers contactless payment by mobile phone.
Terrorist front of course, from the Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about relations between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long-suspected links between the terrorist group al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram seem to be confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel himself confirmed that Algiers had now "gained certainty" about this.
"The way in which both organizations are proceeding, as well as the relations between the intelligence services, point to a clear cooperation," he said, without going into further detail.
Paris seems to be making a similar analysis.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January has brought interfaces to light.
Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory, kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by Aqmi supporters, were allegedly killed the following day at the same time as several of their kidnappers during an operation carried out by the French special forces.
French and Nigerian investigators claim to have found several phone chips belonging to the terrorists in the rubble at the scene.
Terrorist axis
The analysis of the telephone calls leads to several interlocutors stationed in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), the investigators are particularly interested in the numbers of two interlocutors: One number leads to a Nigerian who had spent a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram; the other leads to a man who is considered to be close to the Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but there is no doubt that we need to wait for clearer evidence before we can speak of operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Harem."
"However, it is conceivable".
"It has been known for years that the sect receives financial and intellectual support from outside and that this is increasingly active," says Nigerian researcher Kunle Amuwo.
In recent months, these "support services" have become increasingly evident in their course, as have Boko Harem's speeches and modes of operation, which now point to the involvement of suicide bombers and the use of increasingly complex explosives bearing the same signature as those used by Afmi.
The international community, to start with Washington, has since put pressure on Abuja to take account of the problems caused by Boko Haram.
Indeed, the Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of Illuminati that does not need special attention.
Fast success
Founded in Maiduguri in 2002 in the vicinity of a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist Iman Mohammed Yusuf - which in Haoussa means "Western education is a disgrace" - Boko Haram is pursuing the establishment of an Islamic Emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this destitute region, the merger is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes itself and claims strict adherence to Sharia law, while its affiliated activists are engaged in the fight against the godless central government.
The activists initially targeted churches, bars and authorities.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active with their intensified attacks against the commissariats.
However, Abuja's reaction is, as usual, indifferentiated.
The army surrounds the city, 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, who has been taken prisoner, is killed in prison.
As a result, the sect becomes increasingly radical and leaves its strongholds in the north.
Last Christmas, she claimed responsibility for an attack in Jos that claimed 80 lives, and then another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram is blamed for a suicide bombing that took place at the secured police headquarters in Abuja - the first of its kind.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations becomes a priority international target.
The formation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which is supposed to lead from Mauritania to Nigeria to Somalia, has worried all security experts ever since.
While the Aqmi has occupied Mali and Niger, al-Shabaab's Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Harem appears to be a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting with President Goodluck Jonathan in Nigeria, Alain Juppé warned against Boko harem and expressed his willingness to "share all the clues".
The world according to the Republican presidential candidates
Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry rival in simplifying and ignorance of China, Iraq, and helping Israel.
Can a crisis-ridden America lead a complex world with simple, not to say simple-minded, ideas?
If you listen to the Republican presidential candidates, voters could almost get that impression.
For several days now, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and their associates have repeatedly made their thunderous statements, as well as their statements on foreign policy, the traditional Republican focus.
Slogans are used about China, Iran and aid to Israel, often unsubstantiated in any way.
Mitt Romney, who is the most popular with regard to the appointment of the "Grand Old Party", threatened to summon the Chinese to the WTO, accusing them of "currency manipulation", a leading issue in an America that is extremely irritated by the migration of entire industries to Asia.
Stupid if this is supposed to imply the initiation of a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, former ambassador to China under Obama and the only candidate who seems to have a mature vision of foreign policy, has almost choked his breath over his emotion-flattering behavior.
He had called for a tangible but constructive exchange of talks with Beijing (also Obama's current stance).
But Huntsman is not being listened to, as he is stagnating in the depths of opinion polls.
Reagan's image
Romney had also praised military strikes against Iran if sanctions to stop the nuclear program failed.
"If I am elected, I will put a stop to Iran," he had said.
"If Obama is re-elected, they get the bomb."
He has also promised Israel increased military aid and accused Obama of failing to make commitments to this partner.
For his part, entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second-highest ranked candidate, displays a shameful ignorance of the files.
Recently, he called for countering the Chinese military threat as Beijing "tries to develop a nuclear power" - seemingly ignoring the fact that China has had military nuclear weapons since 1964!
For his part, Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and calls for military strikes against Iran, says he is ready to deploy the American army in Mexico against drug cartels.
Obama's 2009 ban on the use of torture against suspected terrorists was also endorsed by Cain, Perry, and candidate Michele Bachmann.
It is a far cry from John McCain, the Republican candidate in 2008, an outside policy heavyweight.
The current presidential opponents counter that Reagan also had simple ideas and won the Cold War despite all this.
They recall that Obama himself is an amateur and had to add water to his wine when it came to counterterrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naïve dialogue with Iran, the hasty withdrawal of his "boys" from Iraq, his indecisiveness in Libya, which also earned him a reputation for weakness.
However, this hostility is not quite so informal.
The population rather appreciates the positive balance of national security under Obama, which bin Laden has eliminated.
Since Iraq, it has been wary of military interventions that lead to paralysis.
And Obama surprises more appropriately by arguing that America must be economically rebuilt to revive its leadership.
Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs along the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is expected to supply gas to the equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with glamour and glory.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Russia and Germany below sea level, on the Baltic Sea coast under orchestral sound and a gourmet buffet.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart Mark Rutte from the Netherlands symbolically turned the wheel of the valve that transports Russian gas to the Western European grid.
The new gas pipeline is expected to deliver 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas per year to Western Europe through an initial pipeline of 1,224 km in length connecting the St. Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second pipeline, capable of a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of total French consumption - is due to be completed by the end of 2012.
And the eventuality of the construction of a third line on the same route is already hinted at.
For Gazprom, the timely and punctual completion of this enormous structure looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream pipeline will make it possible to supply gas directly to Germany, avoiding any overland route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine).
For this reason, these two countries are losing some of their power: it is now becoming more difficult for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, did not shy away from comparing the Nord Stream pipeline to a "new german-Soviet pact" linked to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically extremely sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by endorsing this Russian project.
This, however, comes at the cost of debilitating European energy, as the project has opened a breach between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to impose its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, which consume heavily gas and are running out of gas reserves.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out the extent to which the major gas contracts are also important from the political and economic point of view.
All this explains the broad smiles of the numerous Gazprom managers in Lubmin regarding the gas supply line.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with concrete sheathing to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at a depth of about 200 m.
During its construction, minefields dating from the Second World War had to be avoided.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The pipe is a long queue of metal, as heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted by anything along its entire length: neither by valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers refrained from doing so, as the Swedes were not keen to see a Russian state company permanently settling at the height of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas outlet in less than a minute," Jens Müller explained.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered by the designers to be unlikely, as the weld seams were estimated to have a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled from a seagoing vessel for external observation purposes and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, is one meter in diameter, is inserted into the interior of the pipeline and moved by the gas pressure.
After three full days of movement through the pipe at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information about possible deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the point of entry, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to realize this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated here (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transmission to this company on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real amount of gas transported," Jens Müller said.
30% of the financing of the gas pipeline construction was secured by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are certain to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea on a sandy, pine-wooded coastline near Lubmin.
The 4.5 metre high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other key figures of the incoming gas before it is forwarded to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per elapsing hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Founded by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give writing a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, elastic band, eggshell pages, aged over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided to launch a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, the company's expert advisor at the time, was tasked with launching the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an ancient production technique called Mole Skin, which refers to a cotton ack used for upholstered benches, for example.
This type of notebook was in high demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object that was considered an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success kicks in.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established themselves with sales of 12.7 million units.
This is a far cry from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were conceived.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to make a phantom image of the buyers, as the notebook inspires business people as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which initially had 12 employees, now employs over 100 people and has had two offices since 2008; one in Milan, the other in New York.
The company sells its notebooks in bookshops, on Internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in city centres and knows how to assert its identity.
"We have followed the zeitgeist and its new writing needs, which persist despite the rise of emails," explained Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the Moleskine company: recently the brand has launched an exhibition called "Detour", in which architects and artists exhibit their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard-print cover on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Benefiting from its success and this cultural zeitgeist, Moleskine was able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, fountain pens, computer cases... The brand has the entire range of articles.
A success that brings envy on the scene: In autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today's Syntegra Capital, and thus opened a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today marks the beginning of the "15th Week of Work for the Disabled".
Despite a targeted public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is always twice as high as the average average: 19% against 9% unemployment of the total population.
Daunting?
"No," stresses Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt association, which organises the 'Week of Work for the Disabled'.
"The progress made in fifteen years has been considerable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high, but three times as high."
"Nevertheless, there is still a lot to do."
However, it must be said that many obstacles persist for disabled unemployed people before they can get a job.
Older people are more likely to be affected: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them do not have a high school diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled people among the 2.3 million students with higher education.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% for the disabled compared with an overall average of 38%.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to return to work and that "go to the heart of the problem," according to Christian Grapin, director general of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the factual brakes.
What remains is the unspoken, the attitudes that develop certainly, but slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the journal La Cité stated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of disabled people" that was "over-represented by people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually poor".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to meet the employment target of 6% disabled workers set out in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, from 2008, refer to a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organisation tasked with collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof: The number of "fee-paying" permanent establishments, as well as the sum of the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which provides for increases in contributions, created strong pressure on companies," explained Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also expresses a real insight, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of establishments with between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
Hazard: "What luck"
Even before they stood up to the Blue Tuesday evenings (20:45), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens had not concealed the pleasure that the friendly brought them.
It would be too far-reaching to claim that there was collusion between them, but the picture speaks symbolic volumes.
Sitting side by side on the podium of the Stade de France, George Leekens and Eden Hazard could well have made peace.
Five months after his attacking player's spirited gesture against Turkey, the Belgium coach had received nothing but praise for himself.
"I am very happy with Eden, his progress and the fact that he is Belgian."
"I want to look ahead," assures the native Liller for his part.
